INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (1,1,'2012-01-06 19:41:13','2012-01-06 19:41:13','Welcome to WordPress. This is your first post. Edit or delete it, then start blogging!','Hello world!','','trash','open','open','','hello-world','','','2012-01-06 21:10:35','2012-01-06 21:10:35','',0,'http://10.21.12.23/wordpress/?p=1',0,'post','',1),(2,1,'2012-01-06 19:41:13','2012-01-06 19:41:13','This is an example page. It\'s different from a blog post because it will stay in one place and will show up in your site navigation (in most themes). Most people start with an About page that introduces them to potential site visitors. It might say something like this:\n\n<blockquote>Hi there! I\'m a bike messenger by day, aspiring actor by night, and this is my blog. I live in Los Angeles, have a great dog named Jack, and I like pi&#241;a coladas. (And gettin\' caught in the rain.)</blockquote>\n\n...or something like this:\n\n<blockquote>The XYZ Doohickey Company was founded in 1971, and has been providing quality doohickies to the public ever since. Located in Gotham City, XYZ employs over 2,000 people and does all kinds of awesome things for the Gotham community.</blockquote>\n\nAs a new WordPress user, you should go to <a href=\"http://10.21.12.23/wordpress/wp-admin/\">your dashboard</a> to delete this page and create new pages for your content. Have fun!','Sample Page','','trash','open','open','','sample-page','','','2012-01-16 20:49:56','2012-01-16 20:49:56','',0,'http://10.21.12.23/wordpress/?page_id=2',0,'page','',0),(3,1,'2012-01-06 19:41:30','0000-00-00 00:00:00','','Auto Draft','','auto-draft','open','open','','','','','2012-01-06 19:41:30','0000-00-00 00:00:00','',0,'http://10.21.12.23/wordpress/?p=3',0,'post','',0),(4,1,'2012-01-06 20:27:02','2012-01-06 20:27:02','The purpose of this document is to make the HTML code produced by the Front-End Development team more predictable and easier to read. Future developers will know where to look when they need to change or debug something, and newcomers, whether permanent Acquity Group employees or subcontractors, can become integrated with our code more easily if they know which conventions to follow.\r\n\r\nGenerally speaking, best practices for coding in XHTML 1.1 still apply when coding in HTML5.  There are also many new elements and features in the HTML5 language, and its companion, CSS3, that are unfortunately only supported in certain modern browsers, so these new features should be avoided when developing for Firefox versions prior to 3.5, Internet Explorer versions prior to 9, desktop Safari versions prior to 4, Blackberry versions prior to 6, and the majority of “feature phones”.  Since the Front-End Development team still supports many of these platforms on a number of projects, these new elements and features are not addressed here.\r\n\r\nMore information about HTML5 and CSS3 features can be found in Mark Pilgrim’s excellent “Dive Into HTML5” guide, published at <a href=\"http://diveintohtml5.org/\">http://diveintohtml5.org/</a>.','1. Overview','','publish','open','open','','1-overview','','','2012-01-12 21:25:35','2012-01-12 21:25:35','',0,'http://10.21.12.23/wordpress/?p=4',0,'post','',0),(5,1,'2012-01-06 20:25:43','2012-01-06 20:25:43','The purpose of this document is to make the HTML code produced by the Front-End Development team more predictable and easier to read. Future developers will know where to look when they need to change or debug something, and newcomers, whether permanent Acquity Group employees or subcontractors, can become integrated with our code more easily if they know which conventions to follow.\n\nGenerally speaking, best practices for coding in XHTML 1.1 still apply when coding in HTML5.  There are also many new elements and features in the HTML5 language, and its companion, CSS3, that are unfortunately only supported in certain modern browsers, so these new features should be avoided when developing for Firefox versions prior to 3.5, Internet Explorer versions prior to 9, desktop Safari versions prior to 4, Blackberry versions prior to 6, and the majority of “feature phones”.  Since the Front-End Development team still supports many of these platforms on a number of projects, these new elements and features are not addressed here.\n\nMore information about HTML5 and CSS3 features can be found in Mark Pilgrim’s excellent “Dive Into HTML5” guide, published at <a href=\"http://diveintohtml5.org/\">http://diveintohtml5.org/</a>.','1. Overview','','inherit','open','open','','4-revision','','','2012-01-06 20:25:43','2012-01-06 20:25:43','',4,'http://10.21.12.23/wordpress/?p=5',0,'revision','',0),(6,1,'2012-01-06 20:27:02','2012-01-06 20:27:02','The purpose of this document is to make the HTML code produced by the Front-End Development team more predictable and easier to read. Future developers will know where to look when they need to change or debug something, and newcomers, whether permanent Acquity Group employees or subcontractors, can become integrated with our code more easily if they know which conventions to follow.\r\n\r\nGenerally speaking, best practices for coding in XHTML 1.1 still apply when coding in HTML5.  There are also many new elements and features in the HTML5 language, and its companion, CSS3, that are unfortunately only supported in certain modern browsers, so these new features should be avoided when developing for Firefox versions prior to 3.5, Internet Explorer versions prior to 9, desktop Safari versions prior to 4, Blackberry versions prior to 6, and the majority of “feature phones”.  Since the Front-End Development team still supports many of these platforms on a number of projects, these new elements and features are not addressed here.\r\n\r\nMore information about HTML5 and CSS3 features can be found in Mark Pilgrim’s excellent “Dive Into HTML5” guide, published at <a href=\"http://diveintohtml5.org/\">http://diveintohtml5.org/</a>.','1. Overview','','inherit','open','open','','4-revision-2','','','2012-01-06 20:27:02','2012-01-06 20:27:02','',4,'http://10.21.12.23/wordpress/?p=6',0,'revision','',0),(7,1,'2012-01-06 20:28:03','2012-01-06 20:28:03','The purpose of this document is to make the HTML code produced by the Front-End Development team more predictable and easier to read. Future developers will know where to look when they need to change or debug something, and newcomers, whether permanent Acquity Group employees or subcontractors, can become integrated with our code more easily if they know which conventions to follow.\n\nGenerally speaking, best practices for coding in XHTML 1.1 still apply when coding in HTML5.  There are also many new elements and features in the HTML5 language, and its companion, CSS3, that are unfortunately only supported in certain modern browsers, so these new features should be avoided when developing for Firefox versions prior to 3.5, Internet Explorer versions prior to 9, desktop Safari versions prior to 4, Blackberry versions prior to 6, and the majority of “feature phones”.  Since the Front-End Development team still supports many of these platforms on a number of projects, these new elements and features are not addressed here.\n\nMore information about HTML5 and CSS3 features can be found in Mark Pilgrim’s excellent “Dive Into HTML5” guide, published at <a href=\"http://diveintohtml5.org/\">http://diveintohtml5.org/</a>.','1. Overview','','inherit','open','open','','4-autosave','','','2012-01-06 20:28:03','2012-01-06 20:28:03','',4,'http://10.21.12.23/wordpress/?p=7',0,'revision','',0),(8,1,'2012-01-06 20:27:49','2012-01-06 20:27:49','The purpose of this document is to make the HTML code produced by the Front-End Development team more predictable and easier to read. Future developers will know where to look when they need to change or debug something, and newcomers, whether permanent Acquity Group employees or subcontractors, can become integrated with our code more easily if they know which conventions to follow.\r\n\r\nGenerally speaking, best practices for coding in XHTML 1.1 still apply when coding in HTML5.  There are also many new elements and features in the HTML5 language, and its companion, CSS3, that are unfortunately only supported in certain modern browsers, so these new features should be avoided when developing for Firefox versions prior to 3.5, Internet Explorer versions prior to 9, desktop Safari versions prior to 4, Blackberry versions prior to 6, and the majority of “feature phones”.  Since the Front-End Development team still supports many of these platforms on a number of projects, these new elements and features are not addressed here.\r\n\r\nMore information about HTML5 and CSS3 features can be found in Mark Pilgrim’s excellent “Dive Into HTML5” guide, published at <a href=\"http://diveintohtml5.org/\">http://diveintohtml5.org/</a>.','1. Overview','','inherit','open','open','','4-revision-3','','','2012-01-06 20:27:49','2012-01-06 20:27:49','',4,'http://10.21.12.23/wordpress/?p=8',0,'revision','',0),(9,1,'2012-01-09 22:19:52','2012-01-09 22:19:52','<p>Use the following naming conventions whenever creating and/or referencing a specific file, folder or variable in your HTML code.</p>\r\n \r\n<h2>3.1 Folders</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li>Each folder with content residing inside it must contain an index.html (or .php, .jsp, etc.) file.</li>\r\n  <li>Sites must be organized in a logical, hierarchical manner that traditionally would follow the navigation/subnavigation taxonomy.  Do not place all files in a single directory.</li>\r\n  <li>Media folders (images, scripts, styles, flash) may be grouped into a “/media” folder under the root directory, to simplify development or backend integration.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>For ease of use, we have put together a Default Project Taxonomy. You can find these files in the subversion repository or on the shared drive.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>3.2 Files</h2>\r\n<p>File names must be all lowercase with multiple word names separated by a dash (-). This is the easiest way to break up URLs into keywords for search engines. There are still certain engines out there that do not recognize the underscore (_) as a delimiter.</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li>Never use spaces in a file name.</li>\r\n  <li>Grouped items will begin with the same word or string (e.g., item-add.html, item-edit.html, item-proc.html). This makes it easier to find related pages.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<h2>3.3 Images</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li>Image files must be placed in a folder called “/images” under the root directory. Different types of images should be grouped together in their respective subfolders (e.g., /buttons, /products, etc.).</li>\r\n  <li>If an image contains a rollover state, the rollover image must have “-on” appended to the name of the original image (e.g., home.gif & home-on.gif).</li>\r\n  <li>For sites that use small thumbnail images to represent larger images, all thumbnail images must reside in a “/thumbnails” folder within its respective directory. All thumbnail images should be named exactly the same as the full-size image file.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<h2>3.4 Standard Folders</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li>JavaScript files must be placed in a folder called “/scripts” in the root directory of the site.</li>\r\n  <li>Stylesheets must be placed in a folder called “/styles” in the root directory of the site. The general stylesheet should be called “global.css”, and if there is a separate stylesheet for printing it should be called “print.css”.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<h2>3.5 Variable Names</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li>All variable names will begin with a lowercase letter (no numbers).</li>\r\n  <li>Multiword names will be separated by a capital letter (e.g. “firstName”).</li>\r\n  <li>Do not use underscores (_) or dashes (-) in variable names.</li>\r\n  <li>Avoid non-descriptive or highly abbreviated variable names.  Spell out what each variable stands for (e.g., “firstName” not “fn”); “i” and “x” are fine as loop iterators, for example.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<h2>3.6 Include Files</h2>\r\n<p>Links to stylesheets must appear as follows:</p>\r\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\"><pre>&lt;link href=\"styles/default.css\" media=\"screen\" rel=\"stylesheet\" type=\"text/css\" /&gt;</pre></div>\r\n<p>Links to JavaScript files must appear as follows:</p>\r\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\"><pre>&lt;script src=\"scripts/script-name.js\" type=\"text/javascript\"&gt;&lt;/script&gt;</pre></div>\r\n\r\n<h2>3.7 Stylesheets</h2>\r\n<p>Standards related to the coding and structure of CSS documents can be found in a separate CSS Coding Standards document.</p>','3. Files, Folders, and Variables','','publish','open','open','','2-html5-specifications','','','2012-01-12 21:26:09','2012-01-12 21:26:09','',0,'http://10.21.12.23/wordpress/?p=9',0,'post','',0),(10,1,'2012-01-06 20:55:08','2012-01-06 20:55:08','<div>\n\nIn order to ensure compatibility with current and future standards-based Web browsers and to take advantage of modern coding practices, particularly on mobile-optimized sites, all pages should be standardized using the <strong>HTML5</strong> document type declaration. Pages that declare a document type must validate to the standard in order to be valid.\n\nListed below are the specifications for ensuring validation to <strong>HTML5</strong>:\n\n</div>\n<div>\n\n<strong>2.1 Well-Formed Documents</strong>\n\nYour HTML documents must contain certain standard tags on the page.  They must contain an HTML DOCTYPE but no longer require an XML DTD or namespace, since the code is no longer based on XML.\n\nThis is the DOCTYPE used by the Front End Development team.\n\nAll of our pages will validate to the HTML5 declaration.\n<div>\n\n&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;\n\n</div>\nThis is your standard &lt;html&gt; tag, which no longer uses the xmlns (XML NameSpace) attribute or the xml:lang. The remaining lang attribute specifies the page’s language by the IANA two-digit language code.\n<div>\n\n&lt;html lang=\"en\"&gt;\n\n</div>\n</div>\n<div>\n\n<strong>2.2 Nested Elements</strong>\n\nCORRECT (all tags nested):\n<div>\n\n&lt;em&gt;Some &lt;strong&gt;bold&lt;/strong&gt; and italic text.&lt;/em&gt;\n\n</div>\nINCORRECT (tags improperly nested):\n<div>\n\n&lt;em&gt;Some &lt;strong&gt;bold and italic text.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;\n\n</div>\n</div>\n<div>\n\n<strong>2.3 Lowercase Names</strong>\n\nIn XHTML, &lt;TABLE&gt; is not the same as &lt;table&gt; because XML is case-sensitive.  In HTML5, you can use either upper or lowercase tags, but we continue to prefer lowercase for legibility and backward-compatibility.\n\nCORRECT (all tags lowercase):\n<div>\n\n&lt;a href=\"mylink.htm\" onclick=\"javascript:action();\"&gt;My Link&lt;/a&gt;\n\n</div>\n<strong></strong>INCORRECT (tags mixed lowercase and uppercase):\n<div>\n\n&lt;A href=\"mylink.htm\" class=\"linked\"&gt;My Link&lt;/A&gt;\n\n&lt;a href=\"myLink.htm\" Class=\"linked\"&gt;My Link&lt;/a&gt;\n\n&lt;a HREF=\"mylink.htm\" CLASS=\"linked\"&gt;My Link&lt;/a&gt;\n\n</div>\n</div>\n<div>\n\n<strong>2.4 Closing Tags</strong>\n\nA non-empty tag is any tag with content between the start and end, such as &lt;a&gt; or &lt;p&gt;.  In XHTML these must all contain proper end tags, and while HTML5 no longer requires these, it remains our preference to use them.\n\n</div>\n<div>\n<h3>2.4.1 Nonempty Elements</h3>\nCORRECT (tags properly closed):\n<div>\n\n&lt;p&gt;My first paragraph&lt;/p&gt;\n\n&lt;p&gt;My second paragraph&lt;/p&gt;\n\n</div>\nINCORRECT (tags not closed):\n<div>\n\n&lt;p&gt;My first paragraph\n\n&lt;p&gt;My second paragraph\n\n</div>\n</div>\n&nbsp;\n<div>\n<h3>2.4.2 Empty Elements</h3>\nAgain, in XHTML all tags must contain proper end tags, even if the element is empty.  HTML5 no longer requires these but does support them, so it remains our preference to use them.\n\nCORRECT (tags properly closed):\n<div>\n\n&lt;hr /&gt;\n\n&lt;img src=\"my-image.jpg\" alt=\"an image\" /&gt;\n\n</div>\nINCORRECT (tags not closed):\n<div>\n\n&lt;hr&gt;\n\n&lt;img src=\"my-image.jpg\" alt=\"an image\"&gt;\n\n</div>\n</div>\n&nbsp;\n<div>\n\n<strong><em><br clear=\"all\" /> </em></strong>2.5 Attribute Values\n\nAll attributes should be properly quoted. In addition, do not use spaces around the equal sign when specifying an attribute value pair.\n\nCORRECT (attributes properly closed):\n<div>\n\n&lt;img src=”my-image.jpg” id=”myimage” alt=”My Image” /&gt;\n\n</div>\nINCORRECT (attributes missing some quotes):\n<div>\n\n&lt;img src=my-image.jpg\" id=myimage alt = \"My Image\" /&gt;\n\n</div>\n</div>\n&nbsp;\n<div>\n\n2.6 Attribute Minimization\n\nAttribute minimization is not recommended. This happens when only the value of the attribute is added to the tag, without the attribute\'s name.\n\nCORRECT (attribute value given):\n<div>\n\n&lt;input type=\"checkbox\" checked=\"checked\" /&gt;\n\n</div>\nINCORRECT (attribute value missing):\n<div>\n\n&lt;input type=\"checkbox\" checked /&gt;\n\n</div>\n</div>\n<strong><em><br clear=\"all\" /> </em></strong>\n<div>\n\n2.7 Name Attribute Deprecation\n\nXHTML 1.0 deprecated the name attribute for a, applet, form, frame, iframe, img, and map elements, but not for button, textarea, select, input, object, param, and meta elements. Instead use a unique id attribute to specify these elements.\n\n</div>\n<strong><br clear=\"all\" /> </strong>\n<h3>2.7.1 Exception</h3>\nDue to the way some of the backend code works with the database, the name attribute needs to be attached to all form fields. Delivery Services and Managed Services use this attribute to identify elements on the page.  In this case, you will need to keep the name attribute in place.\n\nCORRECT (id attribute used):\n<div>\n\n&lt;img src=\"my-image.jpg\" id=\"myimage\" alt=\"My Image\" /&gt;\n\n</div>\nINCORRECT (name attribute used):\n<div>\n\n&lt;img src=\"my-image.jpg\" name=\"myimage\" alt=\"My Image\" /&gt;\n\n</div>','2. HTML5 Specifications','','inherit','open','open','','9-revision','','','2012-01-06 20:55:08','2012-01-06 20:55:08','',9,'http://10.21.12.23/wordpress/?p=10',0,'revision','',0),(11,1,'2012-01-06 20:56:08','2012-01-06 20:56:08','<div>\n\nIn order to ensure compatibility with current and future standards-based Web browsers and to take advantage of modern coding practices, particularly on mobile-optimized sites, all pages should be standardized using the <strong>HTML5</strong> document type declaration. Pages that declare a document type must validate to the standard in order to be valid.\n\nListed below are the specifications for ensuring validation to <strong>HTML5</strong>:\n\n</div>\n<div>\n<h2>2.1 Well-Formed Documents</h2>\nYour HTML documents must contain certain standard tags on the page.  They must contain an HTML DOCTYPE but no longer require an XML DTD or namespace, since the code is no longer based on XML.\n\nThis is the DOCTYPE used by the Front End Development team.\n\nAll of our pages will validate to the HTML5 declaration.\n<div>\n\n&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;\n\n</div>\nThis is your standard &lt;html&gt; tag, which no longer uses the xmlns (XML NameSpace) attribute or the xml:lang. The remaining lang attribute specifies the page’s language by the IANA two-digit language code.\n<div>\n\n&lt;html lang=\"en\"&gt;\n\n</div>\n</div>\n<div>\n<h2>2.2 Nested Elements</h2>\nCORRECT (all tags nested):\n<div>\n\n&lt;em&gt;Some &lt;strong&gt;bold&lt;/strong&gt; and italic text.&lt;/em&gt;\n\n</div>\nINCORRECT (tags improperly nested):\n<div>\n\n&lt;em&gt;Some &lt;strong&gt;bold and italic text.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;\n\n</div>\n</div>\n<div>\n\n2.3 Lowercase Names\n\nIn XHTML, &lt;TABLE&gt; is not the same as &lt;table&gt; because XML is case-sensitive.  In HTML5, you can use either upper or lowercase tags, but we continue to prefer lowercase for legibility and backward-compatibility.\n\nCORRECT (all tags lowercase):\n<div>\n\n&lt;a href=\"mylink.htm\" onclick=\"javascript:action();\"&gt;My Link&lt;/a&gt;\n\n</div>\n<strong></strong>INCORRECT (tags mixed lowercase and uppercase):\n<div>\n\n&lt;A href=\"mylink.htm\" class=\"linked\"&gt;My Link&lt;/A&gt;\n\n&lt;a href=\"myLink.htm\" Class=\"linked\"&gt;My Link&lt;/a&gt;\n\n&lt;a HREF=\"mylink.htm\" CLASS=\"linked\"&gt;My Link&lt;/a&gt;\n\n</div>\n</div>\n<div>\n\n<strong>2.4 Closing Tags</strong>\n\nA non-empty tag is any tag with content between the start and end, such as &lt;a&gt; or &lt;p&gt;.  In XHTML these must all contain proper end tags, and while HTML5 no longer requires these, it remains our preference to use them.\n\n</div>\n<div>\n<h3>2.4.1 Nonempty Elements</h3>\nCORRECT (tags properly closed):\n<div>\n\n&lt;p&gt;My first paragraph&lt;/p&gt;\n\n&lt;p&gt;My second paragraph&lt;/p&gt;\n\n</div>\nINCORRECT (tags not closed):\n<div>\n\n&lt;p&gt;My first paragraph\n\n&lt;p&gt;My second paragraph\n\n</div>\n</div>\n&nbsp;\n<div>\n<h3>2.4.2 Empty Elements</h3>\nAgain, in XHTML all tags must contain proper end tags, even if the element is empty.  HTML5 no longer requires these but does support them, so it remains our preference to use them.\n\nCORRECT (tags properly closed):\n<div>\n\n&lt;hr /&gt;\n\n&lt;img src=\"my-image.jpg\" alt=\"an image\" /&gt;\n\n</div>\nINCORRECT (tags not closed):\n<div>\n\n&lt;hr&gt;\n\n&lt;img src=\"my-image.jpg\" alt=\"an image\"&gt;\n\n</div>\n</div>\n&nbsp;\n<div>\n\n<strong><em><br clear=\"all\" /> </em></strong>2.5 Attribute Values\n\nAll attributes should be properly quoted. In addition, do not use spaces around the equal sign when specifying an attribute value pair.\n\nCORRECT (attributes properly closed):\n<div>\n\n&lt;img src=”my-image.jpg” id=”myimage” alt=”My Image” /&gt;\n\n</div>\nINCORRECT (attributes missing some quotes):\n<div>\n\n&lt;img src=my-image.jpg\" id=myimage alt = \"My Image\" /&gt;\n\n</div>\n</div>\n&nbsp;\n<div>\n\n2.6 Attribute Minimization\n\nAttribute minimization is not recommended. This happens when only the value of the attribute is added to the tag, without the attribute\'s name.\n\nCORRECT (attribute value given):\n<div>\n\n&lt;input type=\"checkbox\" checked=\"checked\" /&gt;\n\n</div>\nINCORRECT (attribute value missing):\n<div>\n\n&lt;input type=\"checkbox\" checked /&gt;\n\n</div>\n</div>\n<strong><em><br clear=\"all\" /> </em></strong>\n<div>\n\n2.7 Name Attribute Deprecation\n\nXHTML 1.0 deprecated the name attribute for a, applet, form, frame, iframe, img, and map elements, but not for button, textarea, select, input, object, param, and meta elements. Instead use a unique id attribute to specify these elements.\n\n</div>\n<strong><br clear=\"all\" /> </strong>\n<h3>2.7.1 Exception</h3>\nDue to the way some of the backend code works with the database, the name attribute needs to be attached to all form fields. Delivery Services and Managed Services use this attribute to identify elements on the page.  In this case, you will need to keep the name attribute in place.\n\nCORRECT (id attribute used):\n<div>\n\n&lt;img src=\"my-image.jpg\" id=\"myimage\" alt=\"My Image\" /&gt;\n\n</div>\nINCORRECT (name attribute used):\n<div>\n\n&lt;img src=\"my-image.jpg\" name=\"myimage\" alt=\"My Image\" /&gt;\n\n</div>','2. HTML5 Specifications','','inherit','open','open','','9-revision-2','','','2012-01-06 20:56:08','2012-01-06 20:56:08','',9,'http://10.21.12.23/wordpress/?p=11',0,'revision','',0),(12,1,'2012-01-06 20:57:33','2012-01-06 20:57:33','<div>\r\n\r\nIn order to ensure compatibility with current and future standards-based Web browsers and to take advantage of modern coding practices, particularly on mobile-optimized sites, all pages should be standardized using the <strong>HTML5</strong> document type declaration. Pages that declare a document type must validate to the standard in order to be valid.\r\n\r\nListed below are the specifications for ensuring validation to <strong>HTML5</strong>:\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n<div>\r\n<h2>2.1 Well-Formed Documents</h2>\r\nYour HTML documents must contain certain standard tags on the page.  They must contain an HTML DOCTYPE but no longer require an XML DTD or namespace, since the code is no longer based on XML.\r\n\r\nThis is the DOCTYPE used by the Front End Development team.\r\n\r\nAll of our pages will validate to the HTML5 declaration.\r\n<div>\r\n\r\n&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;\r\n\r\n</div>\r\nThis is your standard &lt;html&gt; tag, which no longer uses the xmlns (XML NameSpace) attribute or the xml:lang. The remaining lang attribute specifies the page’s language by the IANA two-digit language code.\r\n<div>\r\n\r\n&lt;html lang=\"en\"&gt;\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div>\r\n<h2>2.2 Nested Elements</h2>\r\nCORRECT (all tags nested):\r\n<div>\r\n\r\n&lt;em&gt;Some &lt;strong&gt;bold&lt;/strong&gt; and italic text.&lt;/em&gt;\r\n\r\n</div>\r\nINCORRECT (tags improperly nested):\r\n<div>\r\n\r\n&lt;em&gt;Some &lt;strong&gt;bold and italic text.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div>\r\n<h2>2.3 Lowercase Names</h2>\r\nIn XHTML, &lt;TABLE&gt; is not the same as &lt;table&gt; because XML is case-sensitive.  In HTML5, you can use either upper or lowercase tags, but we continue to prefer lowercase for legibility and backward-compatibility.\r\n\r\nCORRECT (all tags lowercase):\r\n<div>\r\n\r\n&lt;a href=\"mylink.htm\" onclick=\"javascript:action();\"&gt;My Link&lt;/a&gt;\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n<strong></strong>INCORRECT (tags mixed lowercase and uppercase):\r\n<div>\r\n\r\n&lt;A href=\"mylink.htm\" class=\"linked\"&gt;My Link&lt;/A&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;a href=\"myLink.htm\" Class=\"linked\"&gt;My Link&lt;/a&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;a HREF=\"mylink.htm\" CLASS=\"linked\"&gt;My Link&lt;/a&gt;\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div>\r\n<h2>2.4 Closing Tags</h2>\r\nA non-empty tag is any tag with content between the start and end, such as &lt;a&gt; or &lt;p&gt;.  In XHTML these must all contain proper end tags, and while HTML5 no longer requires these, it remains our preference to use them.\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n<div>\r\n<h3>2.4.1 Nonempty Elements</h3>\r\nCORRECT (tags properly closed):\r\n<div>\r\n\r\n&lt;p&gt;My first paragraph&lt;/p&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;p&gt;My second paragraph&lt;/p&gt;\r\n\r\n</div>\r\nINCORRECT (tags not closed):\r\n<div>\r\n\r\n&lt;p&gt;My first paragraph\r\n\r\n&lt;p&gt;My second paragraph\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div>\r\n<h3>2.4.2 Empty Elements</h3>\r\nAgain, in XHTML all tags must contain proper end tags, even if the element is empty.  HTML5 no longer requires these but does support them, so it remains our preference to use them.\r\n\r\nCORRECT (tags properly closed):\r\n<div>\r\n\r\n&lt;hr /&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;img src=\"my-image.jpg\" alt=\"an image\" /&gt;\r\n\r\n</div>\r\nINCORRECT (tags not closed):\r\n<div>\r\n\r\n&lt;hr&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;img src=\"my-image.jpg\" alt=\"an image\"&gt;\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<h2><strong><em></em></strong>2.5 Attribute Values</h2>\r\n<div>\r\n\r\nAll attributes should be properly quoted. In addition, do not use spaces around the equal sign when specifying an attribute value pair.\r\n\r\nCORRECT (attributes properly closed):\r\n<div>\r\n\r\n&lt;img src=”my-image.jpg” id=”myimage” alt=”My Image” /&gt;\r\n\r\n</div>\r\nINCORRECT (attributes missing some quotes):\r\n<div>\r\n\r\n&lt;img src=my-image.jpg\" id=myimage alt = \"My Image\" /&gt;\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div>\r\n<h2>2.6 Attribute Minimization</h2>\r\nAttribute minimization is not recommended. This happens when only the value of the attribute is added to the tag, without the attribute\'s name.\r\n\r\nCORRECT (attribute value given):\r\n<div>\r\n\r\n&lt;input type=\"checkbox\" checked=\"checked\" /&gt;\r\n\r\n</div>\r\nINCORRECT (attribute value missing):\r\n<div>\r\n\r\n&lt;input type=\"checkbox\" checked /&gt;\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div>\r\n<h2>2.7 Name Attribute Deprecation</h2>\r\nXHTML 1.0 deprecated the name attribute for a, applet, form, frame, iframe, img, and map elements, but not for button, textarea, select, input, object, param, and meta elements. Instead use a unique id attribute to specify these elements.\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n<h3>2.7.1 Exception</h3>\r\nDue to the way some of the backend code works with the database, the name attribute needs to be attached to all form fields. Delivery Services and Managed Services use this attribute to identify elements on the page.  In this case, you will need to keep the name attribute in place.\r\n\r\nCORRECT (id attribute used):\r\n<div>\r\n\r\n&lt;img src=\"my-image.jpg\" id=\"myimage\" alt=\"My Image\" /&gt;\r\n\r\n</div>\r\nINCORRECT (name attribute used):\r\n<div>\r\n\r\n&lt;img src=\"my-image.jpg\" name=\"myimage\" alt=\"My Image\" /&gt;\r\n\r\n</div>','2. HTML5 Specifications','','inherit','open','open','','9-revision-3','','','2012-01-06 20:57:33','2012-01-06 20:57:33','',9,'http://10.21.12.23/wordpress/?p=12',0,'revision','',0),(13,1,'2012-01-06 20:58:22','2012-01-06 20:58:22','<div>\r\n\r\nIn order to ensure compatibility with current and future standards-based Web browsers and to take advantage of modern coding practices, particularly on mobile-optimized sites, all pages should be standardized using the <strong>HTML5</strong> document type declaration. Pages that declare a document type must validate to the standard in order to be valid.\r\n\r\nListed below are the specifications for ensuring validation to <strong>HTML5</strong>:\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n<div>\r\n<h2>2.1 Well-Formed Documents</h2>\r\nYour HTML documents must contain certain standard tags on the page.  They must contain an HTML DOCTYPE but no longer require an XML DTD or namespace, since the code is no longer based on XML.\r\n\r\nThis is the DOCTYPE used by the Front End Development team.\r\n\r\nAll of our pages will validate to the HTML5 declaration.\r\n<div>\r\n<blockquote>&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;</blockquote>\r\n</div>\r\nThis is your standard &lt;html&gt; tag, which no longer uses the xmlns (XML NameSpace) attribute or the xml:lang. The remaining lang attribute specifies the page’s language by the IANA two-digit language code.\r\n<div>\r\n\r\n&lt;html lang=\"en\"&gt;\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div>\r\n<h2>2.2 Nested Eleme