mg src=\"my-image.jpg\" alt=\"an image\" /&gt;\r\n\r\n</div>\r\nINCORRECT (tags not closed):\r\n<div>\r\n\r\n&lt;hr&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;img src=\"my-image.jpg\" alt=\"an image\"&gt;\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<h2><strong><em></em></strong>2.5 Attribute Values</h2>\r\n<div>\r\n\r\nAll attributes should be properly quoted. In addition, do not use spaces around the equal sign when specifying an attribute value pair.\r\n\r\nCORRECT (attributes properly closed):\r\n<div>\r\n\r\n&lt;img src=”my-image.jpg” id=”myimage” alt=”My Image” /&gt;\r\n\r\n</div>\r\nINCORRECT (attributes missing some quotes):\r\n<div>\r\n\r\n&lt;img src=my-image.jpg\" id=myimage alt = \"My Image\" /&gt;\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div>\r\n<h2>2.6 Attribute Minimization</h2>\r\nAttribute minimization is not recommended. This happens when only the value of the attribute is added to the tag, without the attribute\'s name.\r\n\r\nCORRECT (attribute value given):\r\n<div>\r\n\r\n&lt;input type=\"checkbox\" checked=\"checked\" /&gt;\r\n\r\n</div>\r\nINCORRECT (attribute value missing):\r\n<div>\r\n\r\n&lt;input type=\"checkbox\" checked /&gt;\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div>\r\n<h2>2.7 Name Attribute Deprecation</h2>\r\nXHTML 1.0 deprecated the name attribute for a, applet, form, frame, iframe, img, and map elements, but not for button, textarea, select, input, object, param, and meta elements. Instead use a unique id attribute to specify these elements.\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n<h3>2.7.1 Exception</h3>\r\nDue to the way some of the backend code works with the database, the name attribute needs to be attached to all form fields. Delivery Services and Managed Services use this attribute to identify elements on the page.  In this case, you will need to keep the name attribute in place.\r\n\r\nCORRECT (id attribute used):\r\n<div>\r\n\r\n&lt;img src=\"my-image.jpg\" id=\"myimage\" alt=\"My Image\" /&gt;\r\n\r\n</div>\r\nINCORRECT (name attribute used):\r\n<div>\r\n\r\n&lt;img src=\"my-image.jpg\" name=\"myimage\" alt=\"My Image\" /&gt;\r\n\r\n</div>','2. HTML5 Specifications','','inherit','open','open','','9-revision-7','','','2012-01-06 21:04:32','2012-01-06 21:04:32','',9,'http://10.21.12.23/wordpress/?p=16',0,'revision','',0),(17,1,'2012-01-06 19:41:13','2012-01-06 19:41:13','Welcome to WordPress. This is your first post. Edit or delete it, then start blogging!','Hello world!','','inherit','open','open','','1-revision','','','2012-01-06 19:41:13','2012-01-06 19:41:13','',1,'http://10.21.12.23/wordpress/?p=17',0,'revision','',0),(18,1,'2012-01-06 21:06:24','2012-01-06 21:06:24','<div>\r\n\r\nIn order to ensure compatibility with current and future standards-based Web browsers and to take advantage of modern coding practices, particularly on mobile-optimized sites, all pages should be standardized using the <strong>HTML5</strong> document type declaration. Pages that declare a document type must validate to the standard in order to be valid.\r\n\r\nListed below are the specifications for ensuring validation to <strong>HTML5</strong>:\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n<div>\r\n<h2>2.1 Well-Formed Documents</h2>\r\nYour HTML documents must contain certain standard tags on the page.  They must contain an HTML DOCTYPE but no longer require an XML DTD or namespace, since the code is no longer based on XML.\r\n\r\nThis is the DOCTYPE used by the Front End Development team.\r\n\r\nAll of our pages will validate to the HTML5 declaration.\r\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\">&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;</div>\r\nThis is your standard &lt;html&gt; tag, which no longer uses the xmlns (XML NameSpace) attribute or the xml:lang. The remaining lang attribute specifies the page’s language by the IANA two-digit language code.\r\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\">&lt;html lang=\"en\"&gt;</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div>\r\n<h2>2.2 Nested Elements</h2>\r\nCORRECT (all tags nested):\r\n<div>\r\n\r\n&lt;em&gt;Some &lt;strong&gt;bold&lt;/strong&gt; and italic text.&lt;/em&gt;\r\n\r\n</div>\r\nINCORRECT (tags improperly nested):\r\n<div>\r\n\