CTYPE used by the Front End Development team.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>All of our pages will validate to the HTML5 declaration.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"exampleCorrect\">&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This is your standard &lt;html&gt; tag, which no longer uses the xmlns (XML NameSpace) attribute or the xml:lang. The remaining lang attribute specifies the page’s language by the IANA two-digit language code.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"exampleCorrect\">&lt;html lang=\"en\"&gt;</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>2.2 Nested Elements</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>CORRECT (all tags nested):</p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"exampleCorrect\">&lt;em&gt;Some &lt;strong&gt;bold&lt;/strong&gt; and italic text.&lt;/em&gt;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>INCORRECT (tags improperly nested):</p>\r\n<p class=\"exampleIncorrect\">&lt;em&gt;Some &lt;strong&gt;bold and italic text.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;</p>\r\n\r\n<div>\r\n<h2>2.3 Lowercase Names</h2>\r\nIn XHTML, &lt;TABLE&gt; is not the same as &lt;table&gt; because XML is case-sensitive.  In HTML5, you can use either upper or lowercase tags, but we continue to prefer lowercase for legibility and backward-compatibility.\r\n\r\nCORRECT (all tags lowercase):\r\n\r\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\">\r\n&lt;a href=\"mylink.htm\" onclick=\"javascript:action();\"&gt;My Link&lt;/a&gt;\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<strong></strong>INCORRECT (tags mixed lowercase and uppercase):\r\n<div class=\"exampleIncorrect\">\r\n&lt;A href=\"mylink.htm\" class=\"linked\"&gt;My Link&lt;/A&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;a href=\"myLink.htm\" Class=\"linked\"&gt;My Link&lt;/a&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;a HREF=\"mylink.htm\" CLASS=\"linked\"&gt;My Link&lt;/a&gt;\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div>\r\n<h2>2.4 Closing Tags</h2>\r\nA non-empty tag is any tag with content between the start and end, such as &lt;a&gt; or &lt;p&gt;.  In XHTML these must all contain proper end tags, and while HTML5 no longer requires these, it remains our preference to use them.\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n<div>\r\n<h3>2.4.1 Nonempty Elements</h3>\r\nCORRECT (tags properly closed):\r\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\">\r\n&lt;p&gt;My first paragraph&lt;/p&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;p&gt;My second paragraph&lt;/p&gt;\r\n</div>\r\nINCORRECT (tags not closed):\r\n<div class=\"exampleIncorrect\">\r\n&lt;p&gt;My first paragraph\r\n\r\n&lt;p&gt;My second paragraph\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div>\r\n<h3>2.4.2 Empty Elements</h3>\r\nAgain, in XHTML all tags must contain proper end tags, even if the element is empty.  HTML5 no longer requires these but does support them, so it remains our preference to use them.\r\n\r\nCORRECT (tags properly closed):\r\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\">\r\n&lt;hr /&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;img src=\"my-image.jpg\" alt=\"an image\" /&gt;\r\n</div>\r\nINCORRECT (tags not closed):\r\n<div class=\"exampleIncorrect\">\r\n&lt;hr&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;img src=\"my-image.jpg\" alt=\"an image\"&gt;\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<h2><strong><em></em></strong>2.5 Attribute Values</h2>\r\n<div>\r\n\r\nAll attributes should be properly quoted. In addition, do not use spaces around the equal sign when specifying an attribute value pair.\r\n\r\nCORRECT (attributes properly closed):\r\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\">\r\n&lt;img src=”my-image.jpg” id=”myimage” alt=”My Image” /&gt;\r\n</div>\r\nINCORRECT (attributes missing some quotes):\r\n<div class=\"exampleIncorrect\">\r\n&lt;img src=my-image.jpg\" id=myimage alt = \"My Image\" /&gt;\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div>\r\n<h2>2.6 Attribute Minimization</h2>\r\nAttribute minimization is not recommended. This happens when only the value of the attribute is added to the tag, without the attribute\'s name.\r\n\r\nCORRECT (attribute value given):\r\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\">\r\n&lt;input type=\"checkbox\" checked=\"checked\" /&gt;\r\n</div>\r\nINCORRECT (attribute value missing):\r\n<div class=\"exampleIncorrect\">\r\n&lt;input type=\"checkbox\" checked /&gt;\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div>\r\n<h2>2.7 Name Attribute Deprecation</h2>\r\nXHTML 1.0 deprecated the name attribute for a, applet, form, frame, iframe, img, and map elements, but not for button, textarea, select, input, object, param, and meta elements. Instead use a unique id attribute to specify these elements.\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n<h3>2.7.1 Exception</h3>\r\nDue to the way some of the backend code works with the database, the name attribute needs to be attached to all form fields. Delivery Services and Managed Services use this attribute to identify elements on the page.  In this case, you will need to keep the name attribute in place.\r\n\r\nCORRECT (id attribute used):\r\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\">\r\n&lt;img src=\"my-image.jpg\" id=\"myimage\" alt=\"My Image\" /&gt;\r\n</div>\r\nINCORRECT (name attribute used):\r\n<div class=\"exampleIncorrect\">\r\n&lt;img src=\"my-image.jpg\" name=\"myimage\" alt=\"My Image\" /&gt;\r\n</div>','2. HTML5 Specifications','','inherit','open','open','','9-revision-15','','','2012-01-09 19:51:32','2012-01-09 19:51:32','',9,'http://10.21.12.23/wordpress/?p=25',0,'revision','',0),(26,1,'2012-01-09 20:30:53','2012-01-09 20:30:53','<p>In order to ensure compatibility with current and future standards-based Web browsers and to take advantage of modern coding practices, particularly on mobile-optimized sites, all pages should be standardized using the <strong>HTML5</strong> document type declaration. Pages that declare a document type must validate to the standard in order to be valid.</p>\n\n<p>Listed below are the specifications for ensuring validation to <strong>HTML5</strong>:</p>\n\n<h2>2.1 Well-Formed Documents</h2>\n\n<p>Your HTML documents must contain certain standard tags on the page.  They must contain an HTML DOCTYPE but no longer require an XML DTD or namespace, since the code is no longer based on XML.</p>\n\n<p>This is the DOCTYPE used by the Front End Development team.</p>\n\n<p>All of our pages will validate to the HTML5 declaration.</p>\n\n<p class=\"exampleCorrect\">&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;</p>\n\n<p>This is your standard &lt;html&gt; tag, which no longer uses the xmlns (XML NameSpace) attribute or the xml:lang. The remaining lang attribute specifies the page’s language by the IANA two-digit language code.</p>\n\n<p class=\"exampleCorrect\">&lt;html lang=\"en\"&gt;</p>\n\n<h2>2.2 Nested Elements</h2>\n\n<p><strong>CORRECT (all tags nested):</strong></p>\n\n<p class=\"exampleCorrect\">&lt;em&gt;Some &lt;strong&gt;bold&lt;/strong&gt; and italic text.&lt;/em&gt;</p>\n\n<p><strong>INCORRECT (tags improperly nested):</strong></p>\n\n<div class=\"exampleIncorrect\">&lt;em&gt;Some &lt;strong&gt;bold and italic text.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;</div>\n\n<h2>2.3 Lowercase Names</h2>\n\n<p>In XHTML, &lt;TABLE&gt; is not the same as &lt;table&gt; because XML is case-sensitive.  In HTML5, you can use either upper or lowercase tags, but we continue to prefer lowercase for legibility and backward-compatibility.</p>\n\n<p><strong>CORRECT (all tags lowercase):</strong></p>\n\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\">&lt;a href=\"mylink.htm\" onclick=\"javascript:action();\"&gt;My Link&lt;/a&gt;</div>\n\n<p><strong>INCORRECT (tags mixed lowercase and uppercase):</strong></p>\n\n<div class=\"exampleIncorrect\">\n&lt;A href=\"mylink.htm\" class=\"linked\"&gt;My Link&lt;/A&gt;\n\n&lt;a href=\"myLink.htm\" Class=\"linked\"&gt;My Link&lt;/a&gt;\n\n&lt;a HREF=\"mylink.htm\" CLASS=\"linked\"&gt;My Link&lt;/a&gt;\n</div>\n\n<h2>2.4 Closing Tags</h2>\n\n<p>A non-empty tag is any tag with content between the start and end, such as &lt;a&gt; or &lt;p&gt;.  In XHTML these must all contain proper end tags, and while HTML5 no longer requires these, it remains our preference to use them.</p>\n\n<h3>2.4.1 Nonempty Elements</h3>\n\n<p><strong>CORRECT (tags properly closed):</strong></p>\n\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\">\n&lt;p&gt;My first paragraph&lt;/p&gt;\n\n&lt;p&gt;My second paragraph&lt;/p&gt;\n</div>\n\n<p><strong>INCORRECT (tags not closed):</strong></p>\n<div class=\"exampleIncorrect\">\n&lt;p&gt;My first paragraph\n\n&lt;p&gt;My second paragraph\n</div>\n\n<h3>2.4.2 Empty Elements</h3>\n\n<p>Again, in XHTML all tags must contain proper end tags, even if the element is empty.  HTML5 no longer requires these but does support them, so it remains our preference to use them.</p>\n\n<p><strong>CORRECT (tags properly closed):</strong></p>\n\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\">\n&lt;hr /&gt;\n\n&lt;img src=\"my-image.jpg\" alt=\"an image\" /&gt;\n</div>\n\n<p><strong>INCORRECT (tags not closed):</strong></p>\n\n<div class=\"exampleIncorrect\">\n&lt;hr&gt;\n\n&lt;img src=\"my-image.jpg\" alt=\"an image\"&gt;\n</div>\n\n<h2>2.5 Attribute Values</h2>\n\n<p>All attributes should be properly quoted. In addition, do not use spaces around the equal sign when specifying an attribute value pair.</p>\n\n<p><strong>CORRECT (attributes properly closed):</strong></p>\n\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\">&lt;img src=”my-image.jpg” id=”myimage” alt=”My Image” /&gt;</div>\n\n<p><strong>INCORRECT (attributes missing some quotes):</strong></p>\n\n<div class=\"exampleIncorrect\">&lt;img src=my-image.jpg\" id=myimage alt = \"My Image\" /&gt;</div>\n\n<h2>2.6 Attribute Minimization</h2>\n\n<p>Attribute minimization is not recommended. This happens when only the value of the attribute is added to the tag, without the attribute\'s name.</p>\n\n<p><strong>CORRECT (attribute value given):</strong></p>\n\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\">&lt;input type=\"checkbox\" checked=\"checked\" /&gt;</div>\n\n<p><strong>INCORRECT (attribute value missing):</strong></p>\n\n<div class=\"exampleIncorrect\">&lt;input type=\"checkbox\" checked /&gt;</div>\n\n<h2>2.7 Name Attribute Deprecation</h2>\n\n<p>XHTML 1.0 deprecated the name attribute for a, applet, form, frame, iframe, img, and map elements, but not for button, textarea, select, input, object, param, and meta elements. Instead use a unique id attribute to specify these elements.</p>\n\n<h3>2.7.1 Exception</h3>\n<p>Due to the way some of the backend code works with the database, the name attribute needs to be attached to all form fields. Delivery Services and Managed Services use this attribute to identify elements on the page.  In this case, you will need to keep the name attribute in place.</p>\n\n<p><strong>CORRECT (id attribute used):</strong></p>\n\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\">&lt;img src=\"my-image.jpg\" id=\"myimage\" alt=\"My Image\" /&gt;</div>\n\n<p><strong>INCORRECT (name attribute used):</strong></p>\n\n<div class=\"exampleIncorrect\">&lt;img src=\"my-image.jpg\" name=\"myimage\" alt=\"My Image\" /&gt;</div>','2. HTML5 Specifications','','inherit','open','open','','9-revision-16','','','2012-01-09 20:30:53','2012-01-09 20:30:53','',9,'http://10.21.12.23/wordpress/?p=26',0,'revision','',0),(27,1,'2012-01-09 22:19:36','2012-01-09 22:19:36','<p>In order to ensure compatibility with current and future standards-based Web browsers and to take advantage of modern coding practices, particularly on mobile-optimized sites, all pages should be standardized using the <strong>HTML5</strong> document type declaration. Pages that declare a document type must validate to the standard in order to be valid.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Listed below are the specifications for ensuring validation to <strong>HTML5</strong>:</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>2.1 Well-Formed Documents</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>Your HTML documents must contain certain standard tags on the page.  They must contain an HTML DOCTYPE but no longer require an XML DTD or namespace, since the code is no longer based on XML.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This is the DOCTYPE used by the Front End Development team.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>All of our pages will validate to the HTML5 declaration.</p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\"><pre>&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;</pre></div>\r\n\r\n<p>This is your standard &lt;html&gt; tag, which no longer uses the xmlns (XML NameSpace) attribute or the xml:lang. The remaining lang attribute specifies the page’s language by the IANA two-digit language code.</p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\"><pre>&lt;html lang=\"en\"&gt;</pre></div>\r\n\r\n<h2>2.2 Nested Elements</h2>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>CORRECT (all tags nested):</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\"><pre>&lt;em&gt;Some &lt;strong&gt;bold&lt;/strong&gt; and italic text.&lt;/em&gt;</pre></div>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>INCORRECT (tags improperly nested):</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"exampleIncorrect\"><pre>&lt;em&gt;Some &lt;strong&gt;bold and italic text.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;</pre></div>\r\n\r\n<h2>2.3 Lowercase Names</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>In XHTML, &lt;TABLE&gt; is not the same as &lt;table&gt; because XML is case-sensitive.  In HTML5, you can use either upper or lowercase tags, but we continue to prefer lowercase for legibility and backward-compatibility.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>CORRECT (all tags lowercase):</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\"><pre>&lt;a href=\"mylink.htm\" onclick=\"javascript:action();\"&gt;My Link&lt;/a&gt;</pre></div>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>INCORRECT (tags mixed lowercase and uppercase):</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"exampleIncorrect\">\r\n<pre>\r\n&lt;A href=\"mylink.htm\" class=\"linked\"&gt;My Link&lt;/A&gt;\r\n&lt;a href=\"myLink.htm\" Class=\"linked\"&gt;My Link&lt;/a&gt;\r\n&lt;a HREF=\"mylink.htm\" CLASS=\"linked\"&gt;My Link&lt;/a&gt;</pre></div>\r\n\r\n<h2>2.4 Closing Tags</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>A non-empty tag is any tag with content between the start and end, such as &lt;a&gt; or &lt;p&gt;.  In XHTML these must all contain proper end tags, and while HTML5 no longer requires these, it remains our preference to use them.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>2.4.1 Nonempty Elements</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>CORRECT (tags properly closed):</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\">\r\n<pre>\r\n&lt;p&gt;My first paragraph&lt;/p&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;My second paragraph&lt;/p&gt;</pre></div>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>INCORRECT (tags not closed):</strong></p>\r\n<div class=\"exampleIncorrect\">\r\n<pre>\r\n&lt;p&gt;My first paragraph\r\n&lt;p&gt;My second paragraph</pre></div>\r\n\r\n<h3>2.4.2 Empty Elements</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Again, in XHTML all tags must contain proper end tags, even if the element is empty.  HTML5 no longer requires these but does support them, so it remains our preference to use them.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>CORRECT (tags properly closed):</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\">\r\n<pre>\r\n&lt;hr /&gt;\r\n&lt;img src=\"my-image.jpg\" alt=\"an image\" /&gt;</pre></div>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>INCORRECT (tags not closed):</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"exampleIncorrect\">\r\n<pre>\r\n&lt;hr&gt;\r\n&lt;img src=\"my-image.jpg\" alt=\"an image\"&gt;</pre></div>\r\n\r\n<h2>2.5 Attribute Values</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>All attributes should be properly quoted. In addition, do not use spaces around the equal sign when specifying an attribute value pair.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>CORRECT (attributes properly closed):</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\"><pre>&lt;img src=”my-image.jpg” id=”myimage” alt=”My Image” /&gt;</pre></div>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>INCORRECT (attributes missing some quotes):</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"exampleIncorrect\"><pre>&lt;img src=my-image.jpg\" id=myimage alt = \"My Image\" /&gt;</pre></div>\r\n\r\n<h2>2.6 Attribute Minimization</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>Attribute minimization is not recommended. This happens when only the value of the attribute is added to the tag, without the attribute\'s name.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>CORRECT (attribute value given):</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\"><pre>&lt;input type=\"checkbox\" checked=\"checked\" /&gt;</pre></div>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>INCORRECT (attribute value missing):</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"exampleIncorrect\"><pre>&lt;input type=\"checkbox\" checked /&gt;</pre></div>\r\n\r\n<h2>2.7 Name Attribute Deprecation</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>XHTML 1.0 deprecated the name attribute for a, applet, form, frame, iframe, img, and map elements, but not for button, textarea, select, input, object, param, and meta elements. Instead use a unique id attribute to specify these elements.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>2.7.1 Exception</h3>\r\n<p>Due to the way some of the backend code works with the database, the name attribute needs to be attached to all form fields. Delivery Services and Managed Services use this attribute to identify elements on the page.  In this case, you will need to keep the name attribute in place.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>CORRECT (id attribute used):</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\"><pre>&lt;img src=\"my-image.jpg\" id=\"myimage\" alt=\"My Image\" /&gt;</pre></div>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>INCORRECT (name attribute used):</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"exampleIncorrect\"><pre>&lt;img src=\"my-image.jpg\" name=\"myimage\" alt=\"My Image\" /&gt;</pre></div>','2. HTML5 Specifications','','publish','open','open','','3-files-folders-and-variables','','','2012-01-12 21:25:51','2012-01-12 21:25:51','',0,'http://10.21.12.23/wordpress/?p=27',0,'post','',0),(28,1,'2012-01-09 22:18:42','2012-01-09 22:18:42','<p>Use the following naming conventions whenever creating and/or referencing a specific file, folder or variable in your HTML code.</p>\n\n<h2>3.1 Folders</h2>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>Each folder with content residing inside it must contain an index.html (or .php, .jsp, etc.) file.</li>\n  <li>Sites must be organized in a logical, hierarchical manner that traditionally would follow the navigation/subnavigation taxonomy.  Do not place all files in a single directory.</li>\n  <li>Media folders (images, scripts, styles, flash) may be grouped into a “/media” folder under the root directory, to simplify development or backend integration.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>For ease of use, we have put together a <strong>Default Project Taxonomy</strong>. You can find these files in the subversion repository or on the shared drive.</p>\n\n<h2>3.2 Files</h2>\n\n<p>File names must be all lowercase with multiple word names separated by a dash (-). This is the easiest way to break up URLs into keywords for search engines. There are still certain engines out there that do not recognize the underscore (_) as a delimiter.</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>Never use spaces, punctuation, or other special characters (other than the dash, as mentioned above) in a file name.</li>\n  <li>Grouped items will begin with the same word or string (e.g., item-add.html, item-edit.html, item-proc.html). This makes it easier to find related pages.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>3.3 Standard Folders</h2>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>Image files must be placed in a folder called “/images” under the root directory. Different types of images should be grouped together in their respective subfolders (e.g., /buttons, /products, etc.).</li>\n  <li>If an image contains a rollover state, the rollover image must have “-on” appended to the name of the original image (e.g., home.gif &amp; home-on.gif).</li>\n  <li>For sites that use small thumbnail images to represent larger images, all thumbnail images must reside in a “/thumbnails” folder within its respective directory. All thumbnail images should be named exactly the same as the full-size image file.</li>\n  <li>JavaScript files must be placed in a folder called “/scripts” in the root directory of the site.</li>\n  <li>Stylesheets must be placed in a folder called “/styles” in the root directory of the site. The general stylesheet should be called “global.css”, and if there is a separate stylesheet for printing it should be called “print.css”.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>3.4 Variable Names</h2>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>All variable names will begin with a lowercase letter (no numbers).</li>\n  <li>Multiword names will be separated by a capital letter (e.g. “firstName”).</li>\n  <li>Do not use underscores (_) or dashes (-) in variable names.</li>\n  <li>Avoid non-descriptive or highly abbreviated variable names.  Spell out what each variable stands for (e.g., “firstName” not “fn”); “i” and “x” are fine as loop iterators, for example.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>3.5 Include Files</h2>\n\n<p>Links to stylesheets must appear as follows:</p>\n\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\">&lt;link href=\"styles/default.css\" media=\"screen\" rel=\"stylesheet\" type=\"text/css\" /&gt;</div>\n\n<p>Links to JavaScript files must appear as follows:</p>\n\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\">&lt;script src=\"scripts/script-name.js\" type=\"text/javascript\"&gt;&lt;/script&gt;</div>\n\n<h2>3.6 Stylesheets</\n\nStandards related to the coding and structure of CSS documents can be found in a separate <strong>CSS Coding Standards</strong> document.','3. Files, Folders, and Variables','','inherit','open','open','','27-revision','','','2012-01-09 22:18:42','2012-01-09 22:18:42','',27,'http://10.21.12.23/wordpress/?p=28',0,'revision','',0),(29,1,'2012-01-09 22:18:57','2012-01-09 22:18:57','<p>Use the following naming conventions whenever creating and/or referencing a specific file, folder or variable in your HTML code.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>3.1 Folders</h2>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li>Each folder with content residing inside it must contain an index.html (or .php, .jsp, etc.) file.</li>\r\n  <li>Sites must be organized in a logical, hierarchical manner that traditionally would follow the navigation/subnavigation taxonomy.  Do not place all files in a single directory.</li>\r\n  <li>Media folders (images, scripts, styles, flash) may be grouped into a “/media” folder under the root directory, to simplify development or backend integration.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>For ease of use, we have put together a <strong>Default Project Taxonomy</strong>. You can find these files in the subversion repository or on the shared drive.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>3.2 Files</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>File names must be all lowercase with multiple word names separated by a dash (-). This is the easiest way to break up URLs into keywords for search engines. There are still certain engines out there that do not recognize the underscore (_) as a delimiter.</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li>Never use spaces, punctuation, or other special characters (other than the dash, as mentioned above) in a file name.</li>\r\n  <li>Grouped items will begin with the same word or string (e.g., item-add.html, item-edit.html, item-proc.html). This makes it easier to find related pages.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<h2>3.3 Standard Folders</h2>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li>Image files must be placed in a folder called “/images” under the root directory. Different types of images should be grouped together in their respective subfolders (e.g., /buttons, /products, etc.).</li>\r\n  <li>If an image contains a rollover state, the rollover image must have “-on” appended to the name of the original image (e.g., home.gif &amp; home-on.gif).</li>\r\n  <li>For sites that use small thumbnail images to represent larger images, all thumbnail images must reside in a “/thumbnails” folder within its respective directory. All thumbnail images should be named exactly the same as the full-size image file.</li>\r\n  <li>JavaScript files must be placed in a folder called “/scripts” in the root directory of the site.</li>\r\n  <li>Stylesheets must be placed in a folder called “/styles” in the root directory of the site. The general stylesheet should be called “global.css”, and if there is a separate stylesheet for printing it should be called “print.css”.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<h2>3.4 Variable Names</h2>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li>All variable names will begin with a lowercase letter (no numbers).</li>\r\n  <li>Multiword names will be separated by a capital letter (e.g. “firstName”).</li>\r\n  <li>Do not use underscores (_) or dashes (-) in variable names.</li>\r\n  <li>Avoid non-descriptive or highly abbreviated variable names.  Spell out what each variable stands for (e.g., “firstName” not “fn”); “i” and “x” are fine as loop iterators, for example.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<h2>3.5 Include Files</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>Links to stylesheets must appear as follows:</p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\">&lt;link href=\"styles/default.css\" media=\"screen\" rel=\"stylesheet\" type=\"text/css\" /&gt;</div>\r\n\r\n<p>Links to JavaScript files must appear as follows:</p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\">&lt;script src=\"scripts/script-name.js\" type=\"text/javascript\"&gt;&lt;/script&gt;</div>\r\n\r\n<h2>3.6 Stylesheets</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>Standards related to the coding and structure of CSS documents can be found in a separate <strong>CSS Coding Standards</strong> document.</p>','3. Files, Folders, and Variables','','inherit','open','open','','27-revision-2','','','2012-01-09 22:18:57','2012-01-09 22:18:57','',27,'http://10.21.12.23/wordpress/?p=29',0,'revision','',0),(30,1,'2012-01-09 20:31:27','2012-01-09 20:31:27','<p>In order to ensure compatibility with current and future standards-based Web browsers and to take advantage of modern coding practices, particularly on mobile-optimized sites, all pages should be standardized using the <strong>HTML5</strong> document type declaration. Pages that declare a document type must validate to the standard in order to be valid.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Listed below are the specifications for ensuring validation to <strong>HTML5</strong>:</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>2.1 Well-Formed Documents</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>Your HTML documents must contain certain standard tags on the page.  They must contain an HTML DOCTYPE but no longer require an XML DTD or namespace, since the code is no longer based on XML.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This is the DOCTYPE used by the Front End Development team.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>All of our pages will validate to the HTML5 declaration.</p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\">&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;</div>\r\n\r\n<p>This is your standard &lt;html&gt; tag, which no longer uses the xmlns (XML NameSpace) attribute or the xml:lang. The remaining lang attribute specifies the page’s language by the IANA two-digit language code.</p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\">&lt;html lang=\"en\"&gt;</div>\r\n\r\n<h2>2.2 Nested Elements</h2>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>CORRECT (all tags nested):</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\">&lt;em&gt;Some &lt;strong&gt;bold&lt;/strong&gt; and italic text.&lt;/em&gt;</div>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>INCORRECT (tags improperly nested):</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"exampleIncorrect\">&lt;em&gt;Some &lt;strong&gt;bold and italic text.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;</div>\r\n\r\n<h2>2.3 Lowercase Names</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>In XHTML, &lt;TABLE&gt; is not the same as &lt;table&gt; because XML is case-sensitive.  In HTML5, you can use either upper or lowercase tags, but we continue to prefer lowercase for legibility and backward-compatibility.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>CORRECT (all tags lowercase):</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\">&lt;a href=\"mylink.htm\" onclick=\"javascript:action();\"&gt;My Link&lt;/a&gt;</div>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>INCORRECT (tags mixed lowercase and uppercase):</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"exampleIncorrect\">\r\n&lt;A href=\"mylink.htm\" class=\"linked\"&gt;My Link&lt;/A&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;a href=\"myLink.htm\" Class=\"linked\"&gt;My Link&lt;/a&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;a HREF=\"mylink.htm\" CLASS=\"linked\"&gt;My Link&lt;/a&gt;\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<h2>2.4 Closing Tags</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>A non-empty tag is any tag with content between the start and end, such as &lt;a&gt; or &lt;p&gt;.  In XHTML these must all contain proper end tags, and while HTML5 no longer requires these, it remains our preference to use them.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>2.4.1 Nonempty Elements</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>CORRECT (tags properly closed):</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\">\r\n&lt;p&gt;My first paragraph&lt;/p&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;p&gt;My second paragraph&lt;/p&gt;\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>INCORRECT (tags not closed):</strong></p>\r\n<div class=\"exampleIncorrect\">\r\n&lt;p&gt;My first paragraph\r\n\r\n&lt;p&gt;My second paragraph\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<h3>2.4.2 Empty Elements</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Again, in XHTML all tags must contain proper end tags, even if the element is empty.  HTML5 no longer requires these but does support them, so it remains our preference to use them.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>CORRECT (tags properly closed):</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\">\r\n&lt;hr /&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;img src=\"my-image.jpg\" alt=\"an image\" /&gt;\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>INCORRECT (tags not closed):</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"exampleIncorrect\">\r\n&lt;hr&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;img src=\"my-image.jpg\" alt=\"an image\"&gt;\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<h2>2.5 Attribute Values</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>All attributes should be properly quoted. In addition, do not use spaces around the equal sign when specifying an attribute value pair.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>CORRECT (attributes properly closed):</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\">&lt;img src=”my-image.jpg” id=”myimage” alt=”My Image” /&gt;</div>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>INCORRECT (attributes missing some quotes):</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"exampleIncorrect\">&lt;img src=my-image.jpg\" id=myimage alt = \"My Image\" /&gt;</div>\r\n\r\n<h2>2.6 Attribute Minimization</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>Attribute minimization is not recommended. This happens when only the value of the attribute is added to the tag, without the attribute\'s name.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>CORRECT (attribute value given):</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\">&lt;input type=\"checkbox\" checked=\"checked\" /&gt;</div>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>INCORRECT (attribute value missing):</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"exampleIncorrect\">&lt;input type=\"checkbox\" checked /&gt;</div>\r\n\r\n<h2>2.7 Name Attribute Deprecation</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>XHTML 1.0 deprecated the name attribute for a, applet, form, frame, iframe, img, and map elements, but not for button, textarea, select, input, object, param, and meta elements. Instead use a unique id attribute to specify these elements.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>2.7.1 Exception</h3>\r\n<p>Due to the way some of the backend code works with the database, the name attribute needs to be attached to all form fields. Delivery Services and Managed Services use this attribute to identify elements on the page.  In this case, you will need to keep the name attribute in place.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>CORRECT (id attribute used):</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\">&lt;img src=\"my-image.jpg\" id=\"myimage\" alt=\"My Image\" /&gt;</div>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>INCORRECT (name attribute used):</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"exampleIncorrect\">&lt;img src=\"my-image.jpg\" name=\"myimage\" alt=\"My Image\" /&gt;</div>','2. HTML5 Specifications','','inherit','open','open','','9-revision-17','','','2012-01-09 20:31:27','2012-01-09 20:31:27','',9,'http://10.21.12.23/wordpress/?p=30',0,'revision','',0),(31,1,'2012-01-09 22:34:15','2012-01-09 22:34:15','<p>Providing real accessibility to disabled users has very little to do with the requirements of the law defined by Section 508 of the Americans with Disabilities Act (ADA). It has much more to do with understanding how these users use the Internet and the limitations and characteristics of the tools that they are required to work with to access the Internet.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>For example, blind users typically use screen readers, such as JAWS, to access websites. Unlike your eye, screen readers cannot “scan” a page for relevant headings or words. They have to read every single word on the page, from top to bottom.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>With that mind, Web developers can begin to understand the importance of accessibility requirements and best practices, such as:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li>Providing a way for users to skip past the navigation at the top of every page</li>\r\n  <li>Providing in-page navigation so that users can find out what\'s on a page without having to hear the whole thing</li>\r\n  <li>Providing a quick way to go back to the top of the page</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>However, these rules of thumb aren’t only applicable for disabled users.  They can also make websites more usable and accessible for non-disabled users. The things we must do for disabled users turn out to be excellent practices for making sites easier to use for all users. To get an idea of how a disabled person will “see” the page, disable Styles and Images in Firefox’s Web Developer toolbar, or use the Fangs Firefox extension.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>4.1 Alt Tags</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>One of the main requirements of Section 508 is that all images must have a textual equivalent. In HTML, this is accomplished using the alt tag. The purpose of the alt tag is to provide a description of the contents of the image for those users who cannot see the image. All images must have an alt tag in order for the page to pass Section 508 requirements.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, not all images convey content relevant information. For example, small images are occasionally used as visual spacers on a page, but contain or convey no relevant information. Such images do not require a description, though they do require an alt tag.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Use the following rules of thumb in creating alt tags for images:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li>All images must have an alt tag</li>\r\n  <li>For images that are decorative or that do not contain relevant information, use an empty alt tag (alt=\"\")</li>\r\n  <li>For images that communicate important content, provide a description of the content of the image.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>CORRECT (descriptive alt tag):</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\">&lt;img alt=\"Photograph of a dog chasing a bunny\"...</div>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>INCORRECT (not descriptive of the content of the image):</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"exampleIncorrect\">\r\n<pre>\r\n&lt;img alt=\"Photo\"...\r\n&lt;img alt=\"Image\"...</pre></div>\r\n\r\n<h2>4.2 Table Headings</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>If you need to use a table to present tabular data, it should have logical headings. The title row (or rows) must use the &lt;th&gt; tag instead of the &lt;td&gt; tag.  For example, the code for the first row of a shopping cart could look as follows:</p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\">\r\n<pre>\r\n&lt;tr&gt;\r\n	&lt;th scope=\"col\"&gt;Item&lt;/th&gt;\r\n	&lt;th scope=\"col\"&gt;Quantity&lt;/th&gt;\r\n	&lt;th scope=\"col\"&gt;Price&lt;/th&gt;\r\n	&lt;th scope=\"col\"&gt;Total&lt;/th&gt;\r\n&lt;/tr&gt;</pre></div>\r\n\r\n<p>You can also use the &lt;th&gt; tag for row headings, if appropriate. The code for the first row of a shopping cart could look as follows:</p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\">\r\n<pre>\r\n&lt;tr&gt;\r\n	&lt;th scope=\"row\"&gt;Item&lt;/th&gt;\r\n	&lt;td&gt;[Item 1]&lt;/td&gt;\r\n	&lt;td&gt;[Item 2]&lt;/td&gt;\r\n	&lt;td&gt;[Item 3]&lt;/td&gt;\r\n	&lt;td&gt;[Item 4]&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;/tr&gt;</pre></div>\r\n\r\n<h2>4.3 Labels</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>The most common technique for making forms more accessible is using &lt;label&gt; tags to identify each form element (text field, checkbox, radio button, etc.). It is recommended to wrap the label around the element, because it is an inline tag, so it can act like the span tag for anchoring CSS styles. Labels can be used for all form elements: checkboxes, radio buttons, select lists, and buttons (though labels are not required for buttons).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Here is the standard code for a text field within a form:</p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\"><pre>&lt;label&gt;Text Box Label &lt;input type=\"text\" name=\"fieldName\" tabindex=\"1” /&gt;&lt;/label&gt;</pre></div>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>NOTE:  As stated above, name is deprecated but we still use it for various reasons.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<h2>4.4 Tab Index</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>The purpose of the tab index is to specify the order in which form elements will be selected when the user presses the tab key. Form elements can be organized so that users can easily tab through the form in any order they wish.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Below is an example of using the tab index for a generic contact form:</p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\">\r\n<pre>\r\n&lt;label&gt;Name &lt;input type=\"text\" name=\"txtName\" tabindex=\"1\" /&gt;&lt;/label&gt;\r\n&lt;label&gt;Email &lt;input type=\"text\" name=\"txtEmail\" tabindex=\"2\" /&gt;&lt;/label&gt;\r\n&lt;label&gt;Phone &lt;input type=\"text\" name=\"txtPhone\" tabindex=\"3\" /&gt;&lt;/label&gt;\r\n&lt;label&gt;Comments &lt;textarea name=\"txtComments\"  tabindex=\"4\" rows=\"8\" cols=\"40\" /&gt;Enter your comments in this box.&lt;/textarea&gt;&lt;/label&gt;</pre></div>\r\n\r\n<h2>4.5 Skip To Content</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>Section 508 requires that “a method shall be provided that permits users to skip repetitive navigation links.” As a result, each page will require a “Skip to content” link at the top that will jump to the content area of the page. To implement this strategy, include the following on the top of every page:</p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\">\r\n<pre>\r\n&lt;!-- Skip to content link for accessibility purposes --&gt;\r\n&lt;a id=\"skip\" href=\"#content\" title=\"Skip to content\"&gt;Skip to content&lt;/a&gt;</pre></div>\r\n\r\n<p>Once you have the link at the top of the page, you will also need to add the following at the beginning of the content area (typically right before the top level heading on the page):</p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\"><pre>&lt;a id=\"content\"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;</pre></div>\r\n\r\n<p>Or, more succinctly, wrap the content area in a DIV with the appropriate ID:</p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\">\r\n<pre>\r\n&lt;div id=\"content\"&gt;…\r\n	The page’s content.\r\n&lt;/div&gt;</pre></div>\r\n\r\n<h2>4.6 Nested Navigation</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>Long pages with a lot of content (a “long” page can be defined as greater than two screens high) are a real challenge for users, especially disabled ones. Screen reading software has no way to “scan” or “skim” pages for relevant headings or specific words but must instead read the entire page word-by-word from top to bottom, thus making long pages become an excruciating endurance test. One way of alleviating these problems is by creating a hierarchical menu at the top of long pages that link to the headings and subheadings used to break up the page. This menu will act as the page\'s \"table of contents,\" allowing users to see an outline of the page before reading it.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Use HTML anchors at each heading and link the in-page navigation menu items to these anchors. Keep in mind a few things about anchors:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li>Anchor names must be words so that both disabled and non-disabled users can understand what the link is (“#sectiontitle” has more meaning to users than “#5” or “#st”).</li>\r\n  <li>Anchor names must be one word (no spaces or underscores) and all lowercase in order to validate</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>Additionally, the end of each major section of a long page must provide a link back to the top of the page. This will help both disabled and non-disabled users by giving them a shortcut back to where they started on the page. From there, they can choose another heading on the page or navigate to another page. Typically, these links will be placed at the end of each topic section. However, some judgment should be used. There is no reason to place the links after every section if the sections are very short. On long pages, there should always be a link to the top of page placed at the bottom of the page.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Below is the example of a Top link:</p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\"><pre>&lt;a href=\"#\"&gt;Top&lt;/a&gt;</pre></div>\r\n\r\n<p>Most browsers accept “#” as a valid link to the top of a page. Screen readers react to the “#” link correctly as well.</p>','4. Accessibility','','publish','open','open','','4-accessibility','','','2012-01-12 21:26:20','2012-01-12 21:26:20','',0,'http://10.21.12.23/wordpress/?p=31',0,'post','',0),(32,1,'2012-01-09 22:33:56','2012-01-09 22:33:56','<p>Providing real accessibility to disabled users has very little to do with the requirements of the law defined by Section 508 of the Americans with Disabilities Act (ADA). It has much more to do with understanding how these users use the Internet and the limitations and characteristics of the tools that they are required to work with to access the Internet.</p>\n\n<p>For example, blind users typically use screen readers, such as JAWS, to access websites. Unlike your eye, screen readers cannot “scan” a page for relevant headings or words. They have to read every single word on the page, from top to bottom.</p>\n\n<p>With that mind, Web developers can begin to understand the importance of accessibility requirements and best practices, such as:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>Providing a way for users to skip past the navigation at the top of every page</li>\n  <li>Providing in-page navigation so that users can find out what\'s on a page without having to hear the whole thing</li>\n  <li>Providing a quick way to go back to the top of the page</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>However, these rules of thumb aren’t only applicable for disabled users.  They can also make websites more usable and accessible for non-disabled users. The things we must do for disabled users turn out to be excellent practices for making sites easier to use for all users. To get an idea of how a disabled person will “see” the page, disable Styles and Images in Firefox’s Web Developer toolbar, or use the Fangs Firefox extension.</p>\n\n<h2>4.1 Alt Tags</h2>\n\n<p>One of the main requirements of Section 508 is that all images must have a textual equivalent. In HTML, this is accomplished using the alt tag. The purpose of the alt tag is to provide a description of the contents of the image for those users who cannot see the image. All images must have an alt tag in order for the page to pass Section 508 requirements.</p>\n\n<p>However, not all images convey content relevant information. For example, small images are occasionally used as visual spacers on a page, but contain or convey no relevant information. Such images do not require a description, though they do require an alt tag.</p>\n\n<p>Use the following rules of thumb in creating alt tags for images:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>All images must have an alt tag</li>\n  <li>For images that are decorative or that do not contain relevant information, use an empty alt tag (alt=\"\")</li>\n  <li>For images that communicate important content, provide a description of the content of the image.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p><strong>CORRECT (descriptive alt tag):</p>\n\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\">&lt;img alt=\"Photograph of a dog chasing a bunny\"...</div>\n\n<p><strong>INCORRECT (not descriptive of the content of the image):</strong></p>\n\n<div class=\"exampleIncorrect\">\n&lt;img alt=\"Photo\"...\n\n&lt;img alt=\"Image\"...\n</div>\n\n<h2>4.2 Table Headings</h2>\n\n<p>If you need to use a table to present tabular data, it should have logical headings. The title row (or rows) must use the &lt;th&gt; tag instead of the &lt;td&gt; tag.  For example, the code for the first row of a shopping cart could look as follows:</p>\n\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\">\n&lt;tr&gt;\n\n&lt;th scope=\"col\"&gt;Item&lt;/th&gt;\n\n&lt;th scope=\"col\"&gt;Quantity&lt;/th&gt;\n\n&lt;th scope=\"col\"&gt;Price&lt;/th&gt;\n\n&lt;th scope=\"col\"&gt;Total&lt;/th&gt;\n\n&lt;/tr&gt;\n</div>\n\n<p>You can also use the &lt;th&gt; tag for row headings, if appropriate. The code for the first row of a shopping cart could look as follows:</p>\n\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\">\n&lt;tr&gt;\n\n&lt;th scope=\"row\"&gt;Item&lt;/th&gt;\n\n&lt;td&gt;[Item 1]&lt;/td&gt;\n\n&lt;td&gt;[Item 2]&lt;/td&gt;\n\n&lt;td&gt;[Item 3]&lt;/td&gt;\n\n&lt;td&gt;[Item 4]&lt;/td&gt;\n\n&lt;/tr&gt;\n</div>\n\n<h2>4.3 Labels</h2>\n\n<p>The most common technique for making forms more accessible is using &lt;label&gt; tags to identify each form element (text field, checkbox, radio button, etc.). It is recommended to wrap the label around the element, because it is an inline tag, so it can act like the span tag for anchoring CSS styles. Labels can be used for all form elements: checkboxes, radio buttons, select lists, and buttons (though labels are not required for buttons).</p>\n\n<p>Here is the standard code for a text field within a form:</p>\n\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\">&lt;label&gt;Text Box Label &lt;input type=\"text\" name=\"fieldName\" tabindex=\"1” /&gt;&lt;/label&gt;</div>\n\n<p><strong>NOTE:  As stated above, name is deprecated but we still use it for various reasons.</strong></p>\n\n<h2>4.4 Tab Index</h2>\n\n<p>The purpose of the tab index is to specify the order in which form elements will be selected when the user presses the tab key. Form elements can be organized so that users can easily tab through the form in any order they wish.</p>\n\n<p>Below is an example of using the tab index for a generic contact form:</p>\n\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\">\n&lt;label&gt;Name &lt;input type=\"text\" name=\"txtName\" tabindex=\"1\" /&gt;&lt;/label&gt;\n\n&lt;label&gt;Email &lt;input type=\"text\" name=\"txtEmail\" tabindex=\"2\" /&gt;&lt;/label&gt;\n\n&lt;label&gt;Phone &lt;input type=\"text\" name=\"txtPhone\" tabindex=\"3\" /&gt;&lt;/label&gt;\n\n&lt;label&gt;Comments &lt;textarea name=\"txtComments\"  tabindex=\"4\" rows=\"8\" cols=\"40\" /&gt;Enter your comments in this box.&lt;/textarea&gt;\n\n&lt;/label&gt;\n</div>\n\n<h2>4.5 Skip To Content</h2>\n\n<p>Section 508 requires that “a method shall be provided that permits users to skip repetitive navigation links.” As a result, each page will require a “Skip to content” link at the top that will jump to the content area of the page. To implement this strategy, include the following on the top of every page:</p>\n\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\">\n&lt;!-- Skip to content link for accessibility purposes --&gt;\n\n&lt;a id=\"skip\" href=\"#content\" title=\"Skip to content\"&gt;Skip to content&lt;/a&gt;\n</div>\n\n<p>Once you have the link at the top of the page, you will also need to add the following at the beginning of the content area (typically right before the top level heading on the page):</p>\n\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\">\n&lt;a id=\"content\"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;\n</div>\n\n<p>Or, more succinctly, wrap the content area in a DIV with the appropriate ID:</p>\n\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\">\n&lt;div id=\"content\"&gt;…\n\nThe page’s content.\n\n&lt;/div&gt;\n</div>\n\n<h2>4.6 Nested Navigation</h2>\n\n<p>Long pages with a lot of content (a “long” page can be defined as greater than two screens high) are a real challenge for users, especially disabled ones. Screen reading software has no way to “scan” or “skim” pages for relevant headings or specific words but must instead read the entire page word-by-word from top to bottom, thus making long pages become an excruciating endurance test. One way of alleviating these problems is by creating a hierarchical menu at the top of long pages that link to the headings and subheadings used to break up the page. This menu will act as the page\'s \"table of contents,\" allowing users to see an outline of the page before reading it.</p>\n\n<p>Use HTML anchors at each heading and link the in-page navigation menu items to these anchors. Keep in mind a few things about anchors:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>Anchor names must be words so that both disabled and non-disabled users can understand what the link is (“#sectiontitle” has more meaning to users than “#5” or “#st”).</li>\n  <li>Anchor names must be one word (no spaces or underscores) and all lowercase in order to validate</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Additionally, the end of each major section of a long page must provide a link back to the top of the page. This will help both disabled and non-disabled users by giving them a shortcut back to where they started on the page. From there, they can choose another heading on the page or navigate to another page. Typically, these links will be placed at the end of each topic section. However, some judgment should be used. There is no reason to place the links after every section if the sections are very short. On long pages, there should always be a link to the top of page placed at the bottom of the page.</p>\n\n<p>Below is the example of a Top link:</p>\n\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\">\n&lt;a href=\"#\"&gt;Top&lt;/a&gt;\n</div>\n\n<p>Most browsers accept “#” as a valid link to the top of a page. Screen readers react to the “#” link correctly as well.','4. Accessibility','','inherit','open','open','','31-revision','','','2012-01-09 22:33:56','2012-01-09 22:33:56','',31,'http://10.21.12.23/wordpress/?p=32',0,'revision','',0),(33,1,'2012-01-09 22:36:56','2012-01-09 22:36:56','<p>The current trend in Web design is a move toward completely CSS-based page layout, and that is how all of our pages will be coded. There are several reasons for this change in philosophy, as listed below:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li>The primary advantage of this approach is device-independent layouts. Pages will display equally well on cell phones, PDAs or traditional browsers. Additionally, visitors using screen readers do not have to wade through countless table cells and spacers to get at the actual content of our pages. This approach also adheres to the philosophy that HTML markup should be structural only, and that all layout and presentation should be handled by CSS styles.</li>\r\n  <li>By removing presentational markup from your pages, redesigns of existing sites and content is much less labor-intensive (and much less expensive). To change the layout of the site, all you need to do is change the style sheets; you do not need to edit the pages themselves at all.</li>\r\n  <li>Using CSS for layouts reduces the file sizes of your pages, as users no longer need to download presentational data with ach page they visit. The stylesheets that control layout are cached by viewers’ browsers. Reduced file size means faster loads and lower hosting costs.</li>\r\n  <li>Using CSS for layouts also makes it extremely easy to maintain visual consistency throughout a site. Since pages use the same CSS document for their layout, they are all formatted the same. This strengthens the brand and makes the site more usable.</li>\r\n  <li>CSS-based layouts can give sites greater visibility in web searches. The structural information present in standards-compliant documents makes it easy for search engines to access and evaluate the information in those documents, and they get indexed more accurately.</li>\r\n  <li>Standards set forth by the W3C are written so that old browsers will still understand the basic structure of your documents. Even if they can\'t understand the newest and coolest additions to the standards (e.g., CSS-based page formatting), they\'ll still be able to display the site contents. The same, of course, applies to robots – systems that collect information from your site on behalf of search engines and other indexers.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>For these reasons and many others, we will be structuring our presentation layer using CSS instead of the traditional table-based design. Instead, tables will be used for displaying tabular data (which is why they exist in the first place).</p>','5. Page Layout','','publish','open','open','','5-page-layout','','','2012-01-12 21:26:31','2012-01-12 21:26:31','',0,'http://10.21.12.23/wordpress/?p=33',0,'post','',0),(34,1,'2012-01-09 22:36:30','2012-01-09 22:36:30','<p>The current trend in Web design is a move toward completely CSS-based page layout, and that is how all of our pages will be coded. There are several reasons for this change in philosophy, as listed below:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>The primary advantage of this approach is device-independent layouts. Pages will display equally well on cell phones, PDAs or traditional browsers. Additionally, visitors using screen readers do not have to wade through countless table cells and spacers to get at the actual content of our pages. This approach also adheres to the philosophy that HTML markup should be structural only, and that all layout and presentation should be handled by CSS styles.</li>\n  <li>By removing presentational markup from your pages, redesigns of existing sites and content is much less labor-intensive (and much less expensive). To change the layout of the site, all you need to do is change the style sheets; you do not need to edit the pages themselves at all.</li>\n  <li>Using CSS for layouts reduces the file sizes of your pages, as users no longer need to download presentational data with ach page they visit. The stylesheets that control layout are cached by viewers’ browsers. Reduced file size means faster loads and lower hosting costs.</li>\n  <li>Using CSS for layouts also makes it extremely easy to maintain visual consistency throughout a site. Since pages use the same CSS document for their layout, they are all formatted the same. This strengthens the brand and makes the site more usable.</li>\n  <li>CSS-based layouts can give sites greater visibility in web searches. The structural information present in standards-compliant documents makes it easy for search engines to access and evaluate the information in those documents, and they get indexed more accurately.</li>\n  <li>Standards set forth by the W3C are written so that old browsers will still understand the basic structure of your documents. Even if they can\'t understand the newest and coolest additions to the standards (e.g., CSS-based page formatting), they’ll still be able to display the site contents. The same, of course, applies to robots – systems that collect information from your site on behalf of search engines and other indexers.</li>\n</ul>\n&nbsp;\n\nFor these reasons and many others, we will be structuring our presentation layer using CSS instead of the traditional table-based design. Instead, tables will be used for displaying tabular data (which is why they exist in the first place).','5. Page Layout','','inherit','open','open','','33-revision','','','2012-01-09 22:36:30','2012-01-09 22:36:30','',33,'http://10.21.12.23/wordpress/?p=34',0,'revision','',0),(35,1,'2012-01-09 22:39:59','2012-01-09 22:39:59','<p>All textual formatting (aside from bold and italics) must be done using styles. Font tags should never be used. To make using styles easier, most commonly used HTML elements (such as &lt;p&gt;, &lt;h1&gt;, etc.) should have predefined styles. Use these elements as the basis for all of your formatting.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>6.1 Default Stylesheet</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>All predefined styles used must be stored in a central stylesheet located at “/styles/global.css”. Be sure to include a link to this file in all pages that you create.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>6.2 Print Stylesheet</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>In addition to the global.css stylesheet, which is used when viewing pages on screen, there must also be a print.css stylesheet used specifically for print. This sheet is automatically accessed by the browser when the user prints the page. The primary difference in the print stylesheet is that it does not print any of the navigational elements or advanced graphical treatments, which are typically not desired in a print document. It also prints the title at the top of the page in order to clearly identify the source of the printed document.</p>','6. Styles','','publish','open','open','','6-styles','','','2012-01-12 21:26:42','2012-01-12 21:26:42','',0,'http://10.21.12.23/wordpress/?p=35',0,'post','',0),(36,1,'2012-01-09 22:39:51','2012-01-09 22:39:51','<p>All textual formatting (aside from bold and italics) must be done using styles. Font tags should never be used. To make using styles easier, most commonly used HTML elements (such as &lt;p&gt;, &lt;h1&gt;, etc.) should have predefined styles. Use these elements as the basis for all of your formatting.</p>\n\n<h2>6.1 Default Stylesheet</h2>\n\n<p>All predefined styles used must be stored in a central stylesheet located at “/styles/global.css”. Be sure to include a link to this file in all pages that you create.</p>\n\n<h2>6.2 Print Stylesheet</h2>\n\n<p>In addition to the global.css stylesheet, which is used when viewing pages on screen, there must also be a print.css stylesheet used specifically for print. This sheet is automatically accessed by the browser when the user prints the page. The primary difference in the print stylesheet is that it does not print any of the navigational elements or advanced graphical treatments, which are typically not desired in a print document. It also prints the title at the top of the page in order to clearly identify the source of the printed document.\n</div>','6. Styles','','inherit','open','open','','35-revision','','','2012-01-09 22:39:51','2012-01-09 22:39:51','',35,'http://10.21.12.23/wordpress/?p=36',0,'revision','',0),(37,1,'2012-01-09 22:56:02','2012-01-09 22:56:02','<h2>7.1 Comments</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>Due to the nature of our templates, code commenting is fairly important.  The longer our pages become, the more difficult they are to read. Using comments in the code can help circumvent that. Each &lt;div&gt; tag must have a closing comment to easily keep track if your relative location in the code.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Use the following format:</p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\">\r\n<pre>\r\n&lt;div class=\"header\"&gt;\r\n	[insert header code here]\r\n&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;!-- /end .header --&gt;</pre></div>\r\n\r\n<h2>7.2 Meta Block</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>The following block of code must be inserted in the &lt;head&gt; tag of each page:</p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\">\r\n<pre>\r\n&lt;meta http-equiv=\"Content-Type\" content=\"text/html; charset=UTF-8\" /&gt;\r\n&lt;meta http-equiv=\"Content-Language\" content=\"en-us\" /&gt;\r\n&lt;meta http-equiv=\"imagetoolbar\" content=\"false\" /&gt;\r\n&lt;meta name=\"MSSmartTagsPreventParsing\" content=\"true\" /&gt;\r\n&lt;meta name=\"robots\" content=\"all\" /&gt;\r\n&lt;meta name=\"author\" content=\"Acquity Group [InteractiveMarketing@acquitygroup.com]\" /&gt;\r\n&lt;meta name=\"copyright\" content=\"Copyright (c) 2010 Acquity Group\" /&gt;\r\n&lt;meta name=\"keywords\" content=\"\" /&gt;\r\n&lt;meta name=\"description\" content=\"\" /&gt;</pre></div>\r\n\r\n<h2>7.3 Line Breaks</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li>Insert line breaks to separate large logical chunks of code (between &lt;head&gt; and &lt;body&gt;, separating &lt;div&gt; tags, etc.).</li>\r\n  <li>Insert a line break between block-level elements (&lt;p&gt;, &lt;h1&gt;, &lt;h2&gt; to &lt;h6&gt;, &lt;ol&gt;, &lt;ul&gt;, &lt;dl&gt;, &lt;div&gt;, &lt;noscript&gt;, &lt;blockquote&gt;, &lt;form&gt;, &lt;hr&gt;, &lt;pre&gt;, &lt;table&gt;, &lt;fieldset&gt;, &lt;address&gt;).</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<h2>7.4 Indentation</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>Indent code that is logically “inside” other code. This includes nested block-level elements, lists, and tables. The indented code must be on its own line and indented by a tab from the beginning of the line.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>7.4.1 Nested block-level elements</h3>\r\n<p>Insert a line break with an indent prior to every block-level start tag that is logically inside of a block-level tag. In the following example, the &lt;h1&gt; block-level tag is indented because it is inside of the &lt;div&gt; block-level tag. The &lt;p&gt; tag is not indented because it is not inside of another block-level element. The &lt;strong&gt; tag does not require line breaks or indentation because it is an inline element, not a block-level element.</p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\">\r\n<pre>\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n	&lt;h1&gt;My Article&lt;/h1&gt;\r\n&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;p&gt;This is an awesome article. You &lt;strong&gt;must&lt;/strong&gt; read it.&lt;/p&gt;</pre></div>\r\n\r\n<h3>7.4.2 Lists</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>The &lt;ol&gt;, &lt;ul&gt; and &lt;dl&gt; list elements are universally defined to be block-level elements. Using the W3C\'s definition of block-level elements, the &lt;li&gt; element could also be categorized as a block-level element.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In applying the above block-level indentation rules to the &lt;ol&gt;, &lt;ul&gt;, &lt;dl&gt;, and &lt;li&gt; elements, you must indent each of those elements as follows:</p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\">\r\n<pre>\r\n&lt;ol&gt;\r\n	&lt;li&gt;Morning\r\n		&lt;ul&gt;\r\n			&lt;li&gt;Wake up.&lt;/li&gt;\r\n			&lt;li&gt;Go to work.&lt;/li&gt;\r\n		&lt;/ul&gt;\r\n	&lt;/li&gt;\r\n	&lt;li&gt;Afternoon\r\n		&lt;ul&gt;\r\n			&lt;li&gt;Eat lunch.&lt;/li&gt;\r\n			&lt;li&gt;Try and stay awake.&lt;/li&gt;\r\n			&lt;li&gt;Go home and watch TV.&lt;/li&gt;\r\n		&lt;/ul&gt;\r\n	&lt;/li&gt;\r\n	&lt;li&gt;Evening&lt;/li&gt;\r\n&lt;/ol&gt;</pre></div>\r\n\r\n<p>As shown above, when embedding a list inside of a list, the outer list\'s end tag must be placed below the embedded list.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>7.4.3 Tables</h3>\r\n<p>The &lt;table&gt; element is universally defined to be a block-level element. Using the W3C\'s definition of block-level elements, the &lt;thead&gt;, &lt;tbody&gt;, and &lt;tr&gt; elements could also be categorized as block-level elements.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In applying the above block-level indentation rules to the &lt;table&gt;, &lt;thead&gt;, &lt;tbody&gt;, and &lt;tr&gt; elements, you must indent each of those elements as follows:</p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\">\r\n<pre>\r\n&lt;table&gt;\r\n	&lt;thead&gt;\r\n		&lt;tr&gt;\r\n			&lt;th&gt;A&lt;/th&gt;\r\n			&lt;th&gt;B&lt;/th&gt;\r\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n	&lt;/thead&gt;\r\n	&lt;tbody&gt;\r\n		&lt;tr&gt;\r\n			&lt;td&gt;one&lt;/td&gt;\r\n			&lt;td&gt;two&lt;/td&gt;\r\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n		&lt;tr&gt;\r\n			&lt;td&gt;three&lt;/td&gt;\r\n			&lt;td&gt;four&lt;/td&gt;\r\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n	&lt;/tbody&gt;\r\n&lt;/table&gt;</pre></div>\r\n\r\n<p>When embedding a table inside of a table (not recommended), apply the table indentation rules recursively.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>7.5 Images</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>Include the alt attribute for all &lt;img&gt; elements. Use alt=\"\" for decorative images. See the Accessibility guidelines above for the reasoning behind this.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>7.6 Other Best Practices</h2>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li>Do not specify precise sizes for text fonts. Instead, use header tags (&lt;h1&gt;, &lt;h2&gt;, etc.) or use styles with font-size values in the em format.</li>\r\n  <li>Whenever possible, use logical inline elements rather than physical inline elements. Logical inline elements: &lt;abbr&gt;, &lt;acronym&gt;, &lt;cite&gt;, &lt;code&gt;, &lt;del&gt;, &lt;dfn&gt;, &lt;div&gt;, &lt;em&gt;, &lt;ins&gt;, &lt;kbd&gt;, &lt;q&gt;, &lt;samp&gt;, &lt;span&gt;, &lt;strong&gt;, &lt;var&gt;</li>\r\n  <li>Physical inline elements: &lt;b&gt;, &lt;big&gt;, &lt;blink&gt;, &lt;font&gt;, &lt;i&gt;, &lt;s&gt;, &lt;small&gt;, &lt;strike&gt;, &lt;sub&gt;, &lt;sup&gt;, &lt;tt&gt;, &lt;u&gt;</li>\r\n  <li>HTML5 adds many new semantic elements and support for &lt;audio&gt;, &lt;canvas&gt;, &lt;video&gt;, and others.  Since these are not yet supported by many older browsers, we recommend using them only in applications where the platform types are consistent, as in Mobile WebKit-only or kiosk applications.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>As emphasized by HTML’s creators, tags should specify what the text is, not how the text should look. Specifying how the text should look can be misleading because different browsers will display text differently.</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li>Whenever linking to another page, whether it be internal or external, use the title attribute to provide a brief description of the page being linked.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\"><pre>&lt;a href=\"index.php\" title=\"Return to homepage\"&gt;Home&lt;/a&gt;</pre></div>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li>If you use the &lt;blink&gt; or &lt;marquee&gt; tags, you will be beaten with a stick. No exceptions.</li>\r\n  <li>Refrain from using frames. They are incompatible with certain browsers. They inhibit navigability, search engine compatibility and printing functionality.</li>\r\n</ul>','7. Miscellaneous','','publish','open','open','','7-miscellaneous','','','2012-01-12 21:26:52','2012-01-12 21:26:52','',0,'http://10.21.12.23/wordpress/?p=37',0,'post','',1),(38,1,'2012-01-09 22:55:08','2012-01-09 22:55:08','<h2>7.1 Comments</h2>\n\n<p>Due to the nature of our templates, code commenting is fairly important.  The longer our pages become, the more difficult they are to read. Using comments in the code can help circumvent that. Each &lt;div&gt; tag must have a closing comment to easily keep track if your relative location in the code.</p>\n\n<p>Use the following format:</p>\n\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\">\n&lt;div&gt;\n\n[insert header code here]\n\n&lt;/div&gt;\n\n&lt;!-- /end .header --&gt;\n</div>\n\n<h2>7.2 Meta Block</h2>\n\n<p>The following block of code must be inserted in the &lt;head&gt; tag of each page:</p>\n\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\">\n&lt;meta http-equiv=\"Content-Type\" content=\"text/html; charset=UTF-8\" /&gt;\n\n&lt;meta http-equiv=\"Content-Language\" content=\"en-us\" /&gt;\n\n&lt;meta http-equiv=\"imagetoolbar\" content=\"false\" /&gt;\n\n&lt;meta name=\"MSSmartTagsPreventParsing\" content=\"true\" /&gt;\n\n&lt;meta name=\"robots\" content=\"all\" /&gt;\n\n&lt;meta name=\"author\" content=\"Acquity Group [InteractiveMarketing@acquitygroup.com]\" /&gt;\n\n&lt;meta name=\"copyright\" content=\"Copyright (c) 2010 Acquity Group\" /&gt;\n\n&lt;meta name=\"keywords\" content=\"\" /&gt;\n\n&lt;meta name=\"description\" content=\"\" /&gt;\n</div>\n\n<h2>7.3 Line Breaks</h2>\n<ul>\n  <li>Insert line breaks to separate large logical chunks of code (between &lt;head&gt; and &lt;body&gt;, separating &lt;div&gt; tags, etc.).</li>\n  <li>Insert a line break between block-level elements (&lt;p&gt;, &lt;h1&gt;, &lt;h2&gt; to &lt;h6&gt;, &lt;ol&gt;, &lt;ul&gt;, &lt;dl&gt;, &lt;div&gt;, &lt;noscript&gt;, &lt;blockquote&gt;, &lt;form&gt;, &lt;hr&gt;, &lt;pre&gt;, &lt;table&gt;, &lt;fieldset&gt;, &lt;address&gt;).</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>7.4 Indentation</h2>\n\n<p>Indent code that is logically “inside” other code. This includes nested block-level elements, lists, and tables. The indented code must be on its own line and indented by a tab from the beginning of the line.</p>\n\n<h3>7.4.1 Nested block-level elements</h3>\n<p>Insert a line break with an indent prior to every block-level start tag that is logically inside of a block-level tag. In the following example, the &lt;h1&gt; block-level tag is indented because it is inside of the &lt;div&gt; block-level tag. The &lt;p&gt; tag is not indented because it is not inside of another block-level element. The &lt;strong&gt; tag does not require line breaks or indentation because it is an inline element, not a block-level element.</p>\n\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\">\n&lt;div&gt;\n\n&lt;h1&gt;My Article&lt;/h1&gt;\n\n&lt;/div&gt;\n\n&lt;p&gt;This is an awesome article. You &lt;strong&gt;must&lt;/strong&gt; read it.&lt;/p&gt;\n</div>\n\n<h3>7.4.2 Lists</h3>\n\n<p>The &lt;ol&gt;, &lt;ul&gt; and &lt;dl&gt; list elements are universally defined to be block-level elements. Using the W3C\'s definition of block-level elements, the &lt;li&gt; element could also be categorized as a block-level element.</p>\n\n<p>In applying the above block-level indentation rules to the &lt;ol&gt;, &lt;ul&gt;, &lt;dl&gt;, and &lt;li&gt; elements, you must indent each of those elements as follows:</p>\n\n<div>\n&lt;ol&gt;\n\n&lt;li&gt;Morning\n\n&lt;ul&gt;\n\n&lt;li&gt;Wake up.&lt;/li&gt;\n\n&lt;li&gt;Go to work.&lt;/li&gt;\n\n&lt;/ul&gt;\n\n&lt;/li&gt;\n\n&lt;li&gt;Afternoon\n\n&lt;ul&gt;\n\n&lt;li&gt;Eat lunch.&lt;/li&gt;\n\n&lt;li&gt;Try and stay awake.&lt;/li&gt;\n\n&lt;li&gt;Go home and watch TV.&lt;/li&gt;\n\n&lt;/ul&gt;\n\n&lt;/li&gt;\n\n&lt;li&gt;Evening&lt;/li&gt;\n\n&lt;/ol&gt;\n</div>\n\n<p>As shown above, when embedding a list inside of a list, the outer list\'s end tag must be placed below the embedded list.</p>\n\n<h3>7.4.3 Tables</h3>\n<p>The &lt;table&gt; element is universally defined to be a block-level element. Using the W3C\'s definition of block-level elements, the &lt;thead&gt;, &lt;tbody&gt;, and &lt;tr&gt; elements could also be categorized as block-level elements.</p>\n\n<p>In applying the above block-level indentation rules to the &lt;table&gt;, &lt;thead&gt;, &lt;tbody&gt;, and &lt;tr&gt; elements, you must indent each of those elements as follows:</p>\n\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\">\n&lt;table&gt;\n\n&lt;thead&gt;\n\n&lt;tr&gt;\n\n&lt;th&gt;A&lt;/th&gt;\n\n&lt;th&gt;B&lt;/th&gt;\n\n&lt;/tr&gt;\n\n&lt;/thead&gt;\n\n&lt;tbody&gt;\n\n&lt;tr&gt;\n\n&lt;td&gt;one&lt;/td&gt;\n\n&lt;td&gt;two&lt;/td&gt;\n\n&lt;/tr&gt;\n\n&lt;tr&gt;\n\n&lt;td&gt;three&lt;/td&gt;\n\n&lt;td&gt;four&lt;/td&gt;\n\n&lt;/tr&gt;\n\n&lt;/tbody&gt;\n\n&lt;/table&gt;\n</div>\n\n<p>When embedding a table inside of a table (not recommended), apply the table indentation rules recursively.</p>\n\n<h2>7.5 Images</h2>\n\n<p>Include the alt attribute for all &lt;img&gt; elements. Use alt=\"\" for decorative images. See the Accessibility guidelines above for the reasoning behind this.</p>\n\n<h2>7.6 Other Best Practices</h2>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>Whenever possible, use header tags (&lt;h1&gt;, &lt;h2&gt;, etc)</li>\n  <li>Whenever possible, use logical inline elements rather than physical inline elements. Logical inline elements: &lt;abbr&gt;, &lt;acronym&gt;, &lt;cite&gt;, &lt;code&gt;, &lt;del&gt;, &lt;dfn&gt;, &lt;div&gt;, &lt;em&gt;, &lt;ins&gt;, &lt;kbd&gt;, &lt;q&gt;, &lt;samp&gt;, &lt;span&gt;, &lt;strong&gt;, &lt;var&gt;</li>\n</ul>\n&nbsp;\n<ul>\n	<li>Physical inline elements: &lt;b&gt;, &lt;big&gt;, &lt;blink&gt;, &lt;font&gt;, &lt;i&gt;, &lt;s&gt;, &lt;small&gt;, &lt;strike&gt;, &lt;sub&gt;, &lt;sup&gt;, &lt;tt&gt;, &lt;u&gt;</li>\n</ul>\n&nbsp;\n<ul>\n	<li>HTML5 adds many new semantic elements and support for &lt;audio&gt;, &lt;canvas&gt;, &lt;video&gt;, and others.  Since these are not yet supported by many older browsers, we recommend using them only in applications where the platform types are consistent, as in Mobile WebKit-only or kiosk applications.</li>\n</ul>\n&nbsp;\n\nAs emphasized by HTML’s creators, tags should specify what the text is, not how the text should look. Specifying how the text should look can be misleading because different browsers will display text differently.\n\n&nbsp;\n<ul>\n	<li>Whenever linking to another page, whether it be internal or external, use the title attribute to provide a brief description of the page being linked.</li>\n</ul>\n<div>\n\n&lt;a href=\"index.php\" title=\"Return to homepage\"&gt;Home&lt;/a&gt;\n\n</div>\n<ul>\n	<li>If you use the &lt;blink&gt; or &lt;marquee&gt; tags, you will be beaten with a stick. No exceptions.</li>\n</ul>\n&nbsp;\n<ul>\n	<li>Refrain from using frames. They are incompatible with certain browsers and most mobile devices. They inhibit navigability, search engine compatibility and printing functionality.</li>\n</ul>','7. Miscellaneous','','inherit','open','open','','37-revision','','','2012-01-09 22:55:08','2012-01-09 22:55:08','',37,'http://10.21.12.23/wordpress/?p=38',0,'revision','',0),(39,1,'2012-01-09 22:58:46','2012-01-09 22:58:46','<p>Informed browser support choices have to be made to provide the best experience for the widest variety of browsers and devices and for users with physical or technological concerns.  Our browser support guidelines list the browsers we test in to ensure visual and functional fidelity, based on factors including market share, technical capabilities, and project or client requirements.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>8.1 Supported Browsers</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>These modern and widely used browsers support complete functionality including design (images and CSS), advanced behaviors (JavaScript), Flash, and other technologies required.  Our internal QA process ensures visual and functional fidelity in these browsers prior to delivery:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li>Internet Explorer 6, 7, and 8 (Windows)</li>\r\n  <li>Firefox 3.0 (Windows / Macintosh)</li>\r\n  <li>Safari 4.0 (Macintosh)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<h2>8.2 Effective Date</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>This browser support language is current as of July 8, 2010.</p>','8. Browser Support','','publish','open','open','','8-browser-support','','','2012-01-12 21:27:01','2012-01-12 21:27:01','',0,'http://10.21.12.23/wordpress/?p=39',0,'post','',1),(40,1,'2012-01-09 22:58:36','2012-01-09 22:58:36','<p>Informed browser support choices have to be made to provide the best experience for the widest variety of browsers and devices and for users with physical or technological concerns.  Our browser support guidelines list the browsers we test in to ensure visual and functional fidelity, based on factors including market share, technical capabilities, and project or client requirements.</p>\n\n<h2>8.1 Supported Browsers</h2>\n\n<p>These modern and widely used browsers support complete functionality including design (images and CSS), advanced behaviors (JavaScript), Flash, and other technologies required.  Our internal QA process ensures visual and functional fidelity in these browsers prior to delivery:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>Internet Explorer 6, 7, and 8 (Windows)</li>\n  <li>Firefox 3.0 (Windows / Macintosh)</li>\n  <li>Safari 4.0 (Macintosh)</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>8.2 Effective Date</\n\nThis browser support language is current as of July 8, 2010.','8. Browser Support','','inherit','open','open','','39-revision','','','2012-01-09 22:58:36','2012-01-09 22:58:36','',39,'http://10.21.12.23/wordpress/?p=40',0,'revision','',0),(41,1,'2012-01-12 20:09:58','2012-01-12 20:09:58','<p>Providing real accessibility to disabled users has very little to do with the requirements of the law defined by Section 508 of the Americans with Disabilities Act (ADA). It has much more to do with understanding how these users use the Internet and the limitations and characteristics of the tools that they are required to work with to access the Internet.</p>\n\n<p>For example, blind users typically use screen readers, such as JAWS, to access websites. Unlike your eye, screen readers cannot “scan” a page for relevant headings or words. They have to read every single word on the page, from top to bottom.</p>\n\n<p>With that mind, Web developers can begin to understand the importance of accessibility requirements and best practices, such as:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>Providing a way for users to skip past the navigation at the top of every page</li>\n  <li>Providing in-page navigation so that users can find out what\'s on a page without having to hear the whole thing</li>\n  <li>Providing a quick way to go back to the top of the page</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>However, these rules of thumb aren’t only applicable for disabled users.  They can also make websites more usable and accessible for non-disabled users. The things we must do for disabled users turn out to be excellent practices for making sites easier to use for all users. To get an idea of how a disabled person will “see” the page, disable Styles and Images in Firefox’s Web Developer toolbar, or use the Fangs Firefox extension.</p>\n\n<h2>4.1 Alt Tags</h2>\n\n<p>One of the main requirements of Section 508 is that all images must have a textual equivalent. In HTML, this is accomplished using the alt tag. The purpose of the alt tag is to provide a description of the contents of the image for those users who cannot see the image. All images must have an alt tag in order for the page to pass Section 508 requirements.</p>\n\n<p>However, not all images convey content relevant information. For example, small images are occasionally used as visual spacers on a page, but contain or convey no relevant information. Such images do not require a description, though they do require an alt tag.</p>\n\n<p>Use the following rules of thumb in creating alt tags for images:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>All images must have an alt tag</li>\n  <li>For images that are decorative or that do not contain relevant information, use an empty alt tag (alt=\"\")</li>\n  <li>For images that communicate important content, provide a description of the content of the image.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p><strong>CORRECT (descriptive alt tag):</strong></p>\n\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\">&lt;img alt=\"Photograph of a dog chasing a bunny\"...</div>\n\n<p><strong>INCORRECT (not descriptive of the content of the image):</strong></p>\n\n<div class=\"exampleIncorrect\">\n<pre>\n&lt;img alt=\"Photo\"...\n&lt;img alt=\"Image\"...</pre></div>\n\n<h2>4.2 Table Headings</h2>\n\n<p>If you need to use a table to present tabular data, it should have logical headings. The title row (or rows) must use the &lt;th&gt; tag instead of the &lt;td&gt; tag.  For example, the code for the first row of a shopping cart could look as follows:</p>\n\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\">\n<pre>\n&lt;tr&gt;\n	&lt;th scope=\"col\"&gt;Item&lt;/th&gt;\n	&lt;th scope=\"col\"&gt;Quantity&lt;/th&gt;\n	&lt;th scope=\"col\"&gt;Price&lt;/th&gt;\n	&lt;th scope=\"col\"&gt;Total&lt;/th&gt;\n&lt;/tr&gt;</pre></div>\n\n<p>You can also use the &lt;th&gt; tag for row headings, if appropriate. The code for the first row of a shopping cart could look as follows:</p>\n\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\">\n<pre>\n&lt;tr&gt;\n	&lt;th scope=\"row\"&gt;Item&lt;/th&gt;\n	&lt;td&gt;[Item 1]&lt;/td&gt;\n	&lt;td&gt;[Item 2]&lt;/td&gt;\n	&lt;td&gt;[Item 3]&lt;/td&gt;\n	&lt;td&gt;[Item 4]&lt;/td&gt;\n&lt;/tr&gt;</pre></div>\n\n<h2>4.3 Labels</h2>\n\n<p>The most common technique for making forms more accessible is using &lt;label&gt; tags to identify each form element (text field, checkbox, radio button, etc.). It is recommended to wrap the label around the element, because it is an inline tag, so it can act like the span tag for anchoring CSS styles. Labels can be used for all form elements: checkboxes, radio buttons, select lists, and buttons (though labels are not required for buttons).</p>\n\n<p>Here is the standard code for a text field within a form:</p>\n\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\"><pre>&lt;label&gt;Text Box Label &lt;input type=\"text\" name=\"fieldName\" tabindex=\"1” /&gt;&lt;/label&gt;</pre></div>\n\n<p><strong>NOTE:  As stated above, name is deprecated but we still use it for various reasons.</strong></p>\n\n<h2>4.4 Tab Index</h2>\n\n<p>The purpose of the tab index is to specify the order in which form elements will be selected when the user presses the tab key. Form elements can be organized so that users can easily tab through the form in any order they wish.</p>\n\n<p>Below is an example of using the tab index for a generic contact form:</p>\n\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\">\n<pre>\n&lt;label&gt;Name &lt;input type=\"text\" name=\"txtName\" tabindex=\"1\" /&gt;&lt;/label&gt;\n&lt;label&gt;Email &lt;input type=\"text\" name=\"txtEmail\" tabindex=\"2\" /&gt;&lt;/label&gt;\n&lt;label&gt;Phone &lt;input type=\"text\" name=\"txtPhone\" tabindex=\"3\" /&gt;&lt;/label&gt;\n&lt;label&gt;Comments &lt;textarea name=\"txtComments\"  tabindex=\"4\" rows=\"8\" cols=\"40\" /&gt;Enter your comments in this box.&lt;/textarea&gt;&lt;/label&gt;</pre></div>\n\n<h2>4.5 Skip To Content</h2>\n\n<p>Section 508 requires that “a method shall be provided that permits users to skip repetitive navigation links.” As a result, each page will require a “Skip to content” link at the top that will jump to the content area of the page. To implement this strategy, include the following on the top of every page:</p>\n\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\">\n<pre>\n&lt;!-- Skip to content link for accessibility purposes --&gt;\n&lt;a id=\"skip\" href=\"#content\" title=\"Skip to content\"&gt;Skip to content&lt;/a&gt;</pre></div>\n\n<p>Once you have the link at the top of the page, you will also need to add the following at the beginning of the content area (typically right before the top level heading on the page):</p>\n\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\"><pre>&lt;a id=\"content\"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;</pre></div>\n\n<p>Or, more succinctly, wrap the content area in a DIV with the appropriate ID:</p>\n\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\">\n<pre>\n&lt;div id=\"content\"&gt;…\n	The page’s content.\n&lt;/div&gt;</pre></div>\n\n<h2>4.6 Nested Navigation</h2>\n\n<p>Long pages with a lot of content (a “long” page can be defined as greater than two screens high) are a real challenge for users, especially disabled ones. Screen reading software has no way to “scan” or “skim” pages for relevant headings or specific words but must instead read the entire page word-by-word from top to bottom, thus making long pages become an excruciating endurance test. One way of alleviating these problems is by creating a hierarchical menu at the top of long pages that link to the headings and subheadings used to break up the page. This menu will act as the page\'s \"table of contents,\" allowing users to see an outline of the page before reading it.</p>\n\n<p>Use HTML anchors at each heading and link the in-page navigation menu items to these anchors. Keep in mind a few things about anchors:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>Anchor names must be words so that both disabled and non-disabled users can understand what the link is (“#sectiontitle” has more meaning to users than “#5” or “#st”).</li>\n  <li>Anchor names must be one word (no spaces or underscores) and all lowercase in order to validate</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Additionally, the end of each major section of a long page must provide a link back to the top of the page. This will help both disabled and non-disabled users by giving them a shortcut back to where they started on the page. From there, they can choose another heading on the page or navigate to another page. Typically, these links will be placed at the end of each topic section. However, some judgment should be used. There is no reason to place the links after every section if the sections are very short. On long pages, there should always be a link to the top of page placed at the bottom of the page.</p>\n\n<p>Below is the example of a Top link:</p>\n\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\"><pre>&lt;a href=\"#\"&gt;Top&lt;/a&gt;</pre></div>\n\n<p>Most browsers accept “#” as a valid link to the top of a page. Screen readers react to the “#” link correctly as well.</p>','4. Accessibility','','inherit','open','open','','31-autosave','','','2012-01-12 20:09:58','2012-01-12 20:09:58','',31,'http://10.21.12.23/wordpress/?p=41',0,'revision','',0),(42,1,'2012-01-09 22:34:15','2012-01-09 22:34:15','<p>Providing real accessibility to disabled users has very little to do with the requirements of the law defined by Section 508 of the Americans with Disabilities Act (ADA). It has much more to do with understanding how these users use the Internet and the limitations and characteristics of the tools that they are required to work with to access the Internet.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>For example, blind users typically use screen readers, such as JAWS, to access websites. Unlike your eye, screen readers cannot “scan” a page for relevant headings or words. They have to read every single word on the page, from top to bottom.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>With that mind, Web developers can begin to understand the importance of accessibility requirements and best practices, such as:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li>Providing a way for users to skip past the navigation at the top of every page</li>\r\n  <li>Providing in-page navigation so that users can find out what\'s on a page without having to hear the whole thing</li>\r\n  <li>Providing a quick way to go back to the top of the page</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>However, these rules of thumb aren’t only applicable for disabled users.  They can also make websites more usable and accessible for non-disabled users. The things we must do for disabled users turn out to be excellent practices for making sites easier to use for all users. To get an idea of how a disabled person will “see” the page, disable Styles and Images in Firefox’s Web Developer toolbar, or use the Fangs Firefox extension.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>4.1 Alt Tags</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>One of the main requirements of Section 508 is that all images must have a textual equivalent. In HTML, this is accomplished using the alt tag. The purpose of the alt tag is to provide a description of the contents of the image for those users who cannot see the image. All images must have an alt tag in order for the page to pass Section 508 requirements.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, not all images convey content relevant information. For example, small images are occasionally used as visual spacers on a page, but contain or convey no relevant information. Such images do not require a description, though they do require an alt tag.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Use the following rules of thumb in creating alt tags for images:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li>All images must have an alt tag</li>\r\n  <li>For images that are decorative or that do not contain relevant information, use an empty alt tag (alt=\"\")</li>\r\n  <li>For images that communicate important content, provide a description of the content of the image.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>CORRECT (descriptive alt tag):</p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\">&lt;img alt=\"Photograph of a dog chasing a bunny\"...</div>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>INCORRECT (not descriptive of the content of the image):</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"exampleIncorrect\">\r\n&lt;img alt=\"Photo\"...\r\n\r\n&lt;img alt=\"Image\"...\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<h2>4.2 Table Headings</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>If you need to use a table to present tabular data, it should have logical headings. The title row (or rows) must use the &lt;th&gt; tag instead of the &lt;td&gt; tag.  For example, the code for the first row of a shopping cart could look as follows:</p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\">\r\n&lt;tr&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;th scope=\"col\"&gt;Item&lt;/th&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;th scope=\"col\"&gt;Quantity&lt;/th&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;th scope=\"col\"&gt;Price&lt;/th&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;th scope=\"col\"&gt;Total&lt;/th&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<p>You can also use the &lt;th&gt; tag for row headings, if appropriate. The code for the first row of a shopping cart could look as follows:</p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\">\r\n&lt;tr&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;th scope=\"row\"&gt;Item&lt;/th&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;td&gt;[Item 1]&lt;/td&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;td&gt;[Item 2]&lt;/td&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;td&gt;[Item 3]&lt;/td&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;td&gt;[Item 4]&lt;/td&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<h2>4.3 Labels</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>The most common technique for making forms more accessible is using &lt;label&gt; tags to identify each form element (text field, checkbox, radio button, etc.). It is recommended to wrap the label around the element, because it is an inline tag, so it can act like the span tag for anchoring CSS styles. Labels can be used for all form elements: checkboxes, radio buttons, select lists, and buttons (though labels are not required for buttons).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Here is the standard code for a text field within a form:</p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\">&lt;label&gt;Text Box Label &lt;input type=\"text\" name=\"fieldName\" tabindex=\"1” /&gt;&lt;/label&gt;</div>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>NOTE:  As stated above, name is deprecated but we still use it for various reasons.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<h2>4.4 Tab Index</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>The purpose of the tab index is to specify the order in which form elements will be selected when the user presses the tab key. Form elements can be organized so that users can easily tab through the form in any order they wish.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Below is an example of using the tab index for a generic contact form:</p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\">\r\n&lt;label&gt;Name &lt;input type=\"text\" name=\"txtName\" tabindex=\"1\" /&gt;&lt;/label&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;label&gt;Email &lt;input type=\"text\" name=\"txtEmail\" tabindex=\"2\" /&gt;&lt;/label&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;label&gt;Phone &lt;input type=\"text\" name=\"txtPhone\" tabindex=\"3\" /&gt;&lt;/label&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;label&gt;Comments &lt;textarea name=\"txtComments\"  tabindex=\"4\" rows=\"8\" cols=\"40\" /&gt;Enter your comments in this box.&lt;/textarea&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;/label&gt;\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<h2>4.5 Skip To Content</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>Section 508 requires that “a method shall be provided that permits users to skip repetitive navigation links.” As a result, each page will require a “Skip to content” link at the top that will jump to the content area of the page. To implement this strategy, include the following on the top of every page:</p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\">\r\n&lt;!-- Skip to content link for accessibility purposes --&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;a id=\"skip\" href=\"#content\" title=\"Skip to content\"&gt;Skip to content&lt;/a&gt;\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<p>Once you have the link at the top of the page, you will also need to add the following at the beginning of the content area (typically right before the top level heading on the page):</p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\">\r\n&lt;a id=\"content\"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<p>Or, more succinctly, wrap the content area in a DIV with the appropriate ID:</p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\">\r\n&lt;div id=\"content\"&gt;…\r\n\r\nThe page’s content.\r\n\r\n&lt;/div&gt;\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<h2>4.6 Nested Navigation</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>Long pages with a lot of content (a “long” page can be defined as greater than two screens high) are a real challenge for users, especially disabled ones. Screen reading software has no way to “scan” or “skim” pages for relevant headings or specific words but must instead read the entire page word-by-word from top to bottom, thus making long pages become an excruciating endurance test. One way of alleviating these problems is by creating a hierarchical menu at the top of long pages that link to the headings and subheadings used to break up the page. This menu will act as the page\'s \"table of contents,\" allowing users to see an outline of the page before reading it.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Use HTML anchors at each heading and link the in-page navigation menu items to these anchors. Keep in mind a few things about anchors:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li>Anchor names must be words so that both disabled and non-disabled users can understand what the link is (“#sectiontitle” has more meaning to users than “#5” or “#st”).</li>\r\n  <li>Anchor names must be one word (no spaces or underscores) and all lowercase in order to validate</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>Additionally, the end of each major section of a long page must provide a link back to the top of the page. This will help both disabled and non-disabled users by giving them a shortcut back to where they started on the page. From there, they can choose another heading on the page or navigate to another page. Typically, these links will be placed at the end of each topic section. However, some judgment should be used. There is no reason to place the links after every section if the sections are very short. On long pages, there should always be a link to the top of page placed at the bottom of the page.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Below is the example of a Top link:</p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\">\r\n&lt;a href=\"#\"&gt;Top&lt;/a&gt;\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<p>Most browsers accept “#” as a valid link to the top of a page. Screen readers react to the “#” link correctly as well.</p>','4. Accessibility','','inherit','open','open','','31-revision-2','','','2012-01-09 22:34:15','2012-01-09 22:34:15','',31,'http://10.21.12.23/wordpress/?p=42',0,'revision','',0),(43,1,'2012-01-10 16:15:42','2012-01-10 16:15:42','<p>Providing real accessibility to disabled users has very little to do with the requirements of the law defined by Section 508 of the Americans with Disabilities Act (ADA). It has much more to do with understanding how these users use the Internet and the limitations and characteristics of the tools that they are required to work with to access the Internet.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>For example, blind users typically use screen readers, such as JAWS, to access websites. Unlike your eye, screen readers cannot “scan” a page for relevant headings or words. They have to read every single word on the page, from top to bottom.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>With that mind, Web developers can begin to understand the importance of accessibility requirements and best practices, such as:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li>Providing a way for users to skip past the navigation at the top of every page</li>\r\n  <li>Providing in-page navigation so that users can find out what\'s on a page without having to hear the whole thing</li>\r\n  <li>Providing a quick way to go back to the top of the page</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>However, these rules of thumb aren’t only applicable for disabled users.  They can also make websites more usable and accessible for non-disabled users. The things we must do for disabled users turn out to be excellent practices for making sites easier to use for all users. To get an idea of how a disabled person will “see” the page, disable Styles and Images in Firefox’s Web Developer toolbar, or use the Fangs Firefox extension.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>4.1 Alt Tags</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>One of the main requirements of Section 508 is that all images must have a textual equivalent. In HTML, this is accomplished using the alt tag. The purpose of the alt tag is to provide a description of the contents of the image for those users who cannot see the image. All images must have an alt tag in order for the page to pass Section 508 requirements.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, not all images convey content relevant information. For example, small images are occasionally used as visual spacers on a page, but contain or convey no relevant information. Such images do not require a description, though they do require an alt tag.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Use the following rules of thumb in creating alt tags for images:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li>All images must have an alt tag</li>\r\n  <li>For images that are decorative or that do not contain relevant information, use an empty alt tag (alt=\"\")</li>\r\n  <li>For images that communicate important content, provide a description of the content of the image.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>CORRECT (descriptive alt tag):</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\">&lt;img alt=\"Photograph of a dog chasing a bunny\"...</div>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>INCORRECT (not descriptive of the content of the image):</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"exampleIncorrect\">\r\n&lt;img alt=\"Photo\"...\r\n\r\n&lt;img alt=\"Image\"...\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<h2>4.2 Table Headings</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>If you need to use a table to present tabular data, it should have logical headings. The title row (or rows) must use the &lt;th&gt; tag instead of the &lt;td&gt; tag.  For example, the code for the first row of a shopping cart could look as follows:</p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\">\r\n&lt;tr&gt;\r\n&lt;th scope=\"col\"&gt;Item&lt;/th&gt;\r\n&lt;th scope=\"col\"&gt;Quantity&lt;/th&gt;\r\n&lt;th scope=\"col\"&gt;Price&lt;/th&gt;\r\n&lt;th scope=\"col\"&gt;Total&lt;/th&gt;\r\n&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<p>You can also use the &lt;th&gt; tag for row headings, if appropriate. The code for the first row of a shopping cart could look as follows:</p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\">\r\n&lt;tr&gt;\r\n&lt;th scope=\"row\"&gt;Item&lt;/th&gt;\r\n&lt;td&gt;[Item 1]&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td&gt;[Item 2]&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td&gt;[Item 3]&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;td&gt;[Item 4]&lt;/td&gt;\r\n&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<h2>4.3 Labels</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>The most common technique for making forms more accessible is using &lt;label&gt; tags to identify each form element (text field, checkbox, radio button, etc.). It is recommended to wrap the label around the element, because it is an inline tag, so it can act like the span tag for anchoring CSS styles. Labels can be used for all form elements: checkboxes, radio buttons, select lists, and buttons (though labels are not required for buttons).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Here is the standard code for a text field within a form:</p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\">&lt;label&gt;Text Box Label &lt;input type=\"text\" name=\"fieldName\" tabindex=\"1” /&gt;&lt;/label&gt;</div>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>NOTE:  As stated above, name is deprecated but we still use it for various reasons.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<h2>4.4 Tab Index</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>The purpose of the tab index is to specify the order in which form elements will be selected when the user presses the tab key. Form elements can be organized so that users can easily tab through the form in any order they wish.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Below is an example of using the tab index for a generic contact form:</p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\">\r\n&lt;label&gt;Name &lt;input type=\"text\" name=\"txtName\" tabindex=\"1\" /&gt;&lt;/label&gt;\r\n&lt;label&gt;Email &lt;input type=\"text\" name=\"txtEmail\" tabindex=\"2\" /&gt;&lt;/label&gt;\r\n&lt;label&gt;Phone &lt;input type=\"text\" name=\"txtPhone\" tabindex=\"3\" /&gt;&lt;/label&gt;\r\n&lt;label&gt;Comments &lt;textarea name=\"txtComments\"  tabindex=\"4\" rows=\"8\" cols=\"40\" /&gt;Enter your comments in this box.&lt;/textarea&gt;\r\n&lt;/label&gt;\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<h2>4.5 Skip To Content</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>Section 508 requires that “a method shall be provided that permits users to skip repetitive navigation links.” As a result, each page will require a “Skip to content” link at the top that will jump to the content area of the page. To implement this strategy, include the following on the top of every page:</p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\">\r\n&lt;!-- Skip to content link for accessibility purposes --&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;a id=\"skip\" href=\"#content\" title=\"Skip to content\"&gt;Skip to content&lt;/a&gt;\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<p>Once you have the link at the top of the page, you will also need to add the following at the beginning of the content area (typically right before the top level heading on the page):</p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\">&lt;a id=\"content\"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;</div>\r\n\r\n<p>Or, more succinctly, wrap the content area in a DIV with the appropriate ID:</p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\">\r\n&lt;div id=\"content\"&gt;…\r\n\r\nThe page’s content.\r\n\r\n&lt;/div&gt;\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<h2>4.6 Nested Navigation</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>Long pages with a lot of content (a “long” page can be defined as greater than two screens high) are a real challenge for users, especially disabled ones. Screen reading software has no way to “scan” or “skim” pages for relevant headings or specific words but must instead read the entire page word-by-word from top to bottom, thus making long pages become an excruciating endurance test. One way of alleviating these problems is by creating a hierarchical menu at the top of long pages that link to the headings and subheadings used to break up the page. This menu will act as the page\'s \"table of contents,\" allowing users to see an outline of the page before reading it.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Use HTML anchors at each heading and link the in-page navigation menu items to these anchors. Keep in mind a few things about anchors:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li>Anchor names must be words so that both disabled and non-disabled users can understand what the link is (“#sectiontitle” has more meaning to users than “#5” or “#st”).</li>\r\n  <li>Anchor names must be one word (no spaces or underscores) and all lowercase in order to validate</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>Additionally, the end of each major section of a long page must provide a link back to the top of the page. This will help both disabled and non-disabled users by giving them a shortcut back to where they started on the page. From there, they can choose another heading on the page or navigate to another page. Typically, these links will be placed at the end of each topic section. However, some judgment should be used. There is no reason to place the links after every section if the sections are very short. On long pages, there should always be a link to the top of page placed at the bottom of the page.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Below is the example of a Top link:</p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\">&lt;a href=\"#\"&gt;Top&lt;/a&gt;</div>\r\n\r\n<p>Most browsers accept “#” as a valid link to the top of a page. Screen readers react to the “#” link correctly as well.</p>','4. Accessibility','','inherit','open','open','','31-revision-3','','','2012-01-10 16:15:42','2012-01-10 16:15:42','',31,'http://10.21.12.23/wordpress/?p=43',0,'revision','',0),(44,1,'2012-01-12 19:56:14','2012-01-12 19:56:14','<h2>7.1 Comments</h2>\n\n<p>Due to the nature of our templates, code commenting is fairly important.  The longer our pages become, the more difficult they are to read. Using comments in the code can help circumvent that. Each &lt;div&gt; tag must have a closing comment to easily keep track if your relative location in the code.</p>\n\n<p>Use the following format:</p>\n\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\">\n<pre>\n&lt;div class=\"header\"&gt;\n	[insert header code here]\n&lt;/div&gt;\n&lt;!-- /end .header --&gt;</pre></div>\n\n<h2>7.2 Meta Block</h2>\n\n<p>The following block of code must be inserted in the &lt;head&gt; tag of each page:</p>\n\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\">\n<pre>\n&lt;meta http-equiv=\"Content-Type\" content=\"text/html; charset=UTF-8\" /&gt;\n&lt;meta http-equiv=\"Content-Language\" content=\"en-us\" /&gt;\n&lt;meta http-equiv=\"imagetoolbar\" content=\"false\" /&gt;\n&lt;meta name=\"MSSmartTagsPreventParsing\" content=\"true\" /&gt;\n&lt;meta name=\"robots\" content=\"all\" /&gt;\n&lt;meta name=\"author\" content=\"Acquity Group [InteractiveMarketing@acquitygroup.com]\" /&gt;\n&lt;meta name=\"copyright\" content=\"Copyright (c) 2010 Acquity Group\" /&gt;\n&lt;meta name=\"keywords\" content=\"\" /&gt;\n&lt;meta name=\"description\" content=\"\" /&gt;</pre></div>\n\n<h2>7.3 Line Breaks</h2>\n<ul>\n  <li>Insert line breaks to separate large logical chunks of code (between &lt;head&gt; and &lt;body&gt;, separating &lt;div&gt; tags, etc.).</li>\n  <li>Insert a line break between block-level elements (&lt;p&gt;, &lt;h1&gt;, &lt;h2&gt; to &lt;h6&gt;, &lt;ol&gt;, &lt;ul&gt;, &lt;dl&gt;, &lt;div&gt;, &lt;noscript&gt;, &lt;blockquote&gt;, &lt;form&gt;, &lt;hr&gt;, &lt;pre&gt;, &lt;table&gt;, &lt;fieldset&gt;, &lt;address&gt;).</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>7.4 Indentation</h2>\n\n<p>Indent code that is logically “inside” other code. This includes nested block-level elements, lists, and tables. The indented code must be on its own line and indented by a tab from the beginning of the line.</p>\n\n<h3>7.4.1 Nested block-level elements</h3>\n<p>Insert a line break with an indent prior to every block-level start tag that is logically inside of a block-level tag. In the following example, the &lt;h1&gt; block-level tag is indented because it is inside of the &lt;div&gt; block-level tag. The &lt;p&gt; tag is not indented because it is not inside of another block-level element. The &lt;strong&gt; tag does not require line breaks or indentation because it is an inline element, not a block-level element.</p>\n\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\">\n<pre>\n&lt;div&gt;\n	&lt;h1&gt;My Article&lt;/h1&gt;\n&lt;/div&gt;\n&lt;p&gt;This is an awesome article. You &lt;strong&gt;must&lt;/strong&gt; read it.&lt;/p&gt;</pre></div>\n\n<h3>7.4.2 Lists</h3>\n\n<p>The &lt;ol&gt;, &lt;ul&gt; and &lt;dl&gt; list elements are universally defined to be block-level elements. Using the W3C\'s definition of block-level elements, the &lt;li&gt; element could also be categorized as a block-level element.</p>\n\n<p>In applying the above block-level indentation rules to the &lt;ol&gt;, &lt;ul&gt;, &lt;dl&gt;, and &lt;li&gt; elements, you must indent each of those elements as follows:</p>\n\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\">\n<pre>\n&lt;ol&gt;\n	&lt;li&gt;Morning\n		&lt;ul&gt;\n			&lt;li&gt;Wake up.&lt;/li&gt;\n			&lt;li&gt;Go to work.&lt;/li&gt;\n		&lt;/ul&gt;\n	&lt;/li&gt;\n	&lt;li&gt;Afternoon\n	&lt;ul&gt;\n&lt;li&gt;Eat lunch.&lt;/li&gt;\n&lt;li&gt;Try and stay awake.&lt;/li&gt;\n&lt;li&gt;Go home and watch TV.&lt;/li&gt;\n&lt;/ul&gt;\n&lt;/li&gt;\n&lt;li&gt;Evening&lt;/li&gt;\n&lt;/ol&gt;</pre></div>\n\n<p>As shown above, when embedding a list inside of a list, the outer list\'s end tag must be placed below the embedded list.</p>\n\n<h3>7.4.3 Tables</h3>\n<p>The &lt;table&gt; element is universally defined to be a block-level element. Using the W3C\'s definition of block-level elements, the &lt;thead&gt;, &lt;tbody&gt;, and &lt;tr&gt; elements could also be categorized as block-level elements.</p>\n\n<p>In applying the above block-level indentation rules to the &lt;table&gt;, &lt;thead&gt;, &lt;tbody&gt;, and &lt;tr&gt; elements, you must indent each of those elements as follows:</p>\n\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\">\n<pre>\n&lt;table&gt;\n	&lt;thead&gt;\n		&lt;tr&gt;\n			&lt;th&gt;A&lt;/th&gt;\n			&lt;th&gt;B&lt;/th&gt;\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\n	&lt;/thead&gt;\n	&lt;tbody&gt;\n		&lt;tr&gt;\n			&lt;td&gt;one&lt;/td&gt;\n			&lt;td&gt;two&lt;/td&gt;\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\n		&lt;tr&gt;\n			&lt;td&gt;three&lt;/td&gt;\n			&lt;td&gt;four&lt;/td&gt;\n		&lt;/tr&gt;\n	&lt;/tbody&gt;\n&lt;/table&gt;</pre></div>\n\n<p>When embedding a table inside of a table (not recommended), apply the table indentation rules recursively.</p>\n\n<h2>7.5 Images</h2>\n\n<p>Include the alt attribute for all &lt;img&gt; elements. Use alt=\"\" for decorative images. See the Accessibility guidelines above for the reasoning behind this.</p>\n\n<h2>7.6 Other Best Practices</h2>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>Whenever possible, use header tags (&lt;h1&gt;, &lt;h2&gt;, etc)</li>\n  <li>Whenever possible, use logical inline elements rather than physical inline elements. Logical inline elements: &lt;abbr&gt;, &lt;acronym&gt;, &lt;cite&gt;, &lt;code&gt;, &lt;del&gt;, &lt;dfn&gt;, &lt;div&gt;, &lt;em&gt;, &lt;ins&gt;, &lt;kbd&gt;, &lt;q&gt;, &lt;samp&gt;, &lt;span&gt;, &lt;strong&gt;, &lt;var&gt;</li>\n  <li>Physical inline elements: &lt;b&gt;, &lt;big&gt;, &lt;blink&gt;, &lt;font&gt;, &lt;i&gt;, &lt;s&gt;, &lt;small&gt;, &lt;strike&gt;, &lt;sub&gt;, &lt;sup&gt;, &lt;tt&gt;, &lt;u&gt;</li>\n  <li>HTML5 adds many new semantic elements and support for &lt;audio&gt;, &lt;canvas&gt;, &lt;video&gt;, and others.  Since these are not yet supported by many older browsers, we recommend using them only in applications where the platform types are consistent, as in Mobile WebKit-only or kiosk applications.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>As emphasized by HTML’s creators, tags should specify what the text is, not how the text should look. Specifying how the text should look can be misleading because different browsers will display text differently.</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>Whenever linking to another page, whether it be internal or external, use the title attribute to provide a brief description of the page being linked.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\"><pre>&lt;a href=\"index.php\" title=\"Return to homepage\"&gt;Home&lt;/a&gt;</pre></div>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>If you use the &lt;blink&gt; or &lt;marquee&gt; tags, you will be beaten with a stick. No exceptions.</li>\n  <li>Refrain from using frames. They are incompatible with certain browsers and most mobile devices. They inhibit navigability, search engine compatibility and printing functionality.</li>\n</ul>','7. Miscellaneous','','inherit','open','open','','37-autosave','','','2012-01-12 19:56:14','2012-01-12 19:56:14','',37,'http://10.21.12.23/wordpress/?p=44',0,'revision','',0),(45,1,'2012-01-09 22:56:02','2012-01-09 22:56:02','<h2>7.1 Comments</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>Due to the nature of our templates, code commenting is fairly important.  The longer our pages become, the more difficult they are to read. Using comments in the code can help circumvent that. Each &lt;div&gt; tag must have a closing comment to easily keep track if your relative location in the code.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Use the following format:</p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\">\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n\r\n[insert header code here]\r\n\r\n&lt;/div&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;!-- /end .header --&gt;\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<h2>7.2 Meta Block</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>The following block of code must be inserted in the &lt;head&gt; tag of each page:</p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\">\r\n&lt;meta http-equiv=\"Content-Type\" content=\"text/html; charset=UTF-8\" /&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;meta http-equiv=\"Content-Language\" content=\"en-us\" /&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;meta http-equiv=\"imagetoolbar\" content=\"false\" /&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;meta name=\"MSSmartTagsPreventParsing\" content=\"true\" /&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;meta name=\"robots\" content=\"all\" /&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;meta name=\"author\" content=\"Acquity Group [InteractiveMarketing@acquitygroup.com]\" /&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;meta name=\"copyright\" content=\"Copyright (c) 2010 Acquity Group\" /&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;meta name=\"keywords\" content=\"\" /&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;meta name=\"description\" content=\"\" /&gt;\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<h2>7.3 Line Breaks</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li>Insert line breaks to separate large logical chunks of code (between &lt;head&gt; and &lt;body&gt;, separating &lt;div&gt; tags, etc.).</li>\r\n  <li>Insert a line break between block-level elements (&lt;p&gt;, &lt;h1&gt;, &lt;h2&gt; to &lt;h6&gt;, &lt;ol&gt;, &lt;ul&gt;, &lt;dl&gt;, &lt;div&gt;, &lt;noscript&gt;, &lt;blockquote&gt;, &lt;form&gt;, &lt;hr&gt;, &lt;pre&gt;, &lt;table&gt;, &lt;fieldset&gt;, &lt;address&gt;).</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<h2>7.4 Indentation</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>Indent code that is logically “inside” other code. This includes nested block-level elements, lists, and tables. The indented code must be on its own line and indented by a tab from the beginning of the line.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>7.4.1 Nested block-level elements</h3>\r\n<p>Insert a line break with an indent prior to every block-level start tag that is logically inside of a block-level tag. In the following example, the &lt;h1&gt; block-level tag is indented because it is inside of the &lt;div&gt; block-level tag. The &lt;p&gt; tag is not indented because it is not inside of another block-level element. The &lt;strong&gt; tag does not require line breaks or indentation because it is an inline element, not a block-level element.</p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\">\r\n&lt;div&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;h1&gt;My Article&lt;/h1&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;/div&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;p&gt;This is an awesome article. You &lt;strong&gt;must&lt;/strong&gt; read it.&lt;/p&gt;\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<h3>7.4.2 Lists</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>The &lt;ol&gt;, &lt;ul&gt; and &lt;dl&gt; list elements are universally defined to be block-level elements. Using the W3C\'s definition of block-level elements, the &lt;li&gt; element could also be categorized as a block-level element.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In applying the above block-level indentation rules to the &lt;ol&gt;, &lt;ul&gt;, &lt;dl&gt;, and &lt;li&gt; elements, you must indent each of those elements as follows:</p>\r\n\r\n<div>\r\n&lt;ol&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;li&gt;Morning\r\n\r\n&lt;ul&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;li&gt;Wake up.&lt;/li&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;li&gt;Go to work.&lt;/li&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;/ul&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;/li&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;li&gt;Afternoon\r\n\r\n&lt;ul&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;li&gt;Eat lunch.&lt;/li&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;li&gt;Try and stay awake.&lt;/li&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;li&gt;Go home and watch TV.&lt;/li&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;/ul&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;/li&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;li&gt;Evening&lt;/li&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;/ol&gt;\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<p>As shown above, when embedding a list inside of a list, the outer list\'s end tag must be placed below the embedded list.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>7.4.3 Tables</h3>\r\n<p>The &lt;table&gt; element is universally defined to be a block-level element. Using the W3C\'s definition of block-level elements, the &lt;thead&gt;, &lt;tbody&gt;, and &lt;tr&gt; elements could also be categorized as block-level elements.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In applying the above block-level indentation rules to the &lt;table&gt;, &lt;thead&gt;, &lt;tbody&gt;, and &lt;tr&gt; elements, you must indent each of those elements as follows:</p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\">\r\n&lt;table&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;thead&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;tr&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;th&gt;A&lt;/th&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;th&gt;B&lt;/th&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;/thead&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;tbody&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;tr&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;td&gt;one&lt;/td&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;td&gt;two&lt;/td&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;tr&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;td&gt;three&lt;/td&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;td&gt;four&lt;/td&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;/tr&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;/tbody&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;/table&gt;\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<p>When embedding a table inside of a table (not recommended), apply the table indentation rules recursively.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>7.5 Images</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>Include the alt attribute for all &lt;img&gt; elements. Use alt=\"\" for decorative images. See the Accessibility guidelines above for the reasoning behind this.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>7.6 Other Best Practices</h2>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li>Whenever possible, use header tags (&lt;h1&gt;, &lt;h2&gt;, etc)</li>\r\n  <li>Whenever possible, use logical inline elements rather than physical inline elements. Logical inline elements: &lt;abbr&gt;, &lt;acronym&gt;, &lt;cite&gt;, &lt;code&gt;, &lt;del&gt;, &lt;dfn&gt;, &lt;div&gt;, &lt;em&gt;, &lt;ins&gt;, &lt;kbd&gt;, &lt;q&gt;, &lt;samp&gt;, &lt;span&gt;, &lt;strong&gt;, &lt;var&gt;</li>\r\n  <li>Physical inline elements: &lt;b&gt;, &lt;big&gt;, &lt;blink&gt;, &lt;font&gt;, &lt;i&gt;, &lt;s&gt;, &lt;small&gt;, &lt;strike&gt;, &lt;sub&gt;, &lt;sup&gt;, &lt;tt&gt;, &lt;u&gt;</li>\r\n  <li>HTML5 adds many new semantic elements and support for &lt;audio&gt;, &lt;canvas&gt;, &lt;video&gt;, and others.  Since these are not yet supported by many older browsers, we recommend using them only in applications where the platform types are consistent, as in Mobile WebKit-only or kiosk applications.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>As emphasized by HTML’s creators, tags should specify what the text is, not how the text should look. Specifying how the text should look can be misleading because different browsers will display text differently.</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li>Whenever linking to another page, whether it be internal or external, use the title attribute to provide a brief description of the page being linked.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\">\r\n&lt;a href=\"index.php\" title=\"Return to homepage\"&gt;Home&lt;/a&gt;\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li>If you use the &lt;blink&gt; or &lt;marquee&gt; tags, you will be beaten with a stick. No exceptions.</li>\r\n  <li>Refrain from using frames. They are incompatible with certain browsers and most mobile devices. They inhibit navigability, search engine compatibility and printing functionality.</li>\r\n</ul>','7. Miscellaneous','','inherit','open','open','','37-revision-2','','','2012-01-09 22:56:02','2012-01-09 22:56:02','',37,'http://10.21.12.23/wordpress/?p=45',0,'revision','',0),(46,1,'2012-01-12 19:48:56','2012-01-12 19:48:56','<h2>7.1 Com