l>\r\n  <li>All variable names will begin with a lowercase letter (no numbers).</li>\r\n  <li>Multiword names will be separated by a capital letter (e.g. “firstName”).</li>\r\n  <li>Do not use underscores (_) or dashes (-) in variable names.</li>\r\n  <li>Avoid non-descriptive or highly abbreviated variable names.  Spell out what each variable stands for (e.g., “firstName” not “fn”); “i” and “x” are fine as loop iterators, for example.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<h2>3.5 Include Files</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>Links to stylesheets must appear as follows:</p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\"><pre>&lt;link href=\"styles/default.css\" media=\"screen\" rel=\"stylesheet\" type=\"text/css\" /&gt;</pre></div>\r\n\r\n<p>Links to JavaScript files must appear as follows:</p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"exampleCorrect\"><pre>&lt;script src=\"scripts/script-name.js\" type=\"text/javascript\"&gt;&lt;/script&gt;</pre></div>\r\n\r\n<h2>3.6 Stylesheets</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>Standards related to the coding and structure of CSS documents can be found in a separate <strong>CSS Coding Standards</strong> document.</p>','2. HTML5 Specifications','','inherit','open','open','','9-revision-20','','','2012-01-12 20:15:19','2012-01-12 20:15:19','',9,'http://10.21.12.23/wordpress/?p=57',0,'revision','',0),(58,1,'2012-01-12 20:15:53','2012-01-12 20:15:53','<p>In order to ensure compatibility with current and future standards-based Web browsers and to take advantage of modern coding practices, particularly on mobile-optimized sites, all pages should be standardized using the <strong>HTML5</strong> document type declaration. Pages that declare a document type must validate to the standard in order to be valid.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Listed below are the specifications for ensuring validation to <strong>HTML5</strong>:</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>2.1 Well-Formed Documents</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>Your HTML documents must contain certain standard tags on the page.  They must contain an HTML DOCTYPE but no longer require an XML DTD or namespace, since the cod