INSERT INTO `wp_comments` VALUES (1,1,'Mr WordPress','','http://wordpress.org/','','2012-01-06 19:41:13','2012-01-06 19:41:13','Hi, this is a comment.<br />To delete a comment, just log in and view the post&#039;s comments. There you will have the option to edit or delete them.',0,'post-trashed','','',0,0),(2,37,'Bill','bill.corrigan@acquitygroup.com','','127.0.0.1','2012-01-12 20:56:06','2012-01-12 20:56:06','New first bullet for 7.6:\r\n•	Do not specify precise sizes for text fonts. Instead, use header tags (<h1>, <h2>, etc.) or use styles with font-size values in the em format.\r\n\r\nChange this text:\r\n•	Refrain from using frames. They are incompatible with certain browsers. They inhibit navigability, search engine compatibility and printing functionality.\r\n\r\nTo:\r\n•	Refrain from using frames. They are incompatible with certain browsers and most mobile devices. They inhibit navigability, search engine compatibility and printing functionality.',0,'trash','Mozilla/5.0 (Macintosh; Intel Mac OS X 10.6; rv:9.0.1) Gecko/20100101 Firefox/9.0.1','',0,1),(3,37,'Bill','bill.corrigan@acquitygroup.com','','127.0.0.1','2012-01-12 21:06:58','2012-01-12 21:06:58','New first bullet for section 7.6:\r\nDo not specify precise sizes for text fonts. Instead, use header tags (&lt;h1&gt;, &lt;h2&gt;, etc.) or use styles with font-size values in the em format.\r\n\r\nChange this line:\r\nRefrain from using frames. They are incompatible with certain browsers. They inhibit navigability, search engine compatibility and printing functionality.\r\n\r\nTo this:\r\nRefrain from using frames. They are incompatible with certain browsers and most mobile devices. They inhibit navigability, search engine compatibility and printing functionality.',0,'trash','Mozilla/5.0 (Macintosh; Intel Mac OS X 10.6; rv:9.0.1) Gecko/20100101 Firefox/9.0.1','',0,1),(4,37,'Bill','bill.corrigan@acquitygroup.com','','127.0.0.1','2012-01-12 21:17:47','2012-01-12 21:17:47','Change first bullet for section 7.6 from this:\r\n•	Do not specify precise sizes for text fonts. Instead, use header tags (<h1>, <h2>, etc.) or use styles with font-size values in the em format.\r\n\r\nTo this:\r\n•	Whenever possible, use header tags (<h1>, <h2>, etc)\r\n\r\nChange this line:\r\n•	Refrain from using frames. They are incompatible with certain browsers. They inhibit navigability, search engine compatibility and printing functionality.\r\n\r\nTo this:\r\n•	Refrain from using frames. They are incompatible with certain browsers and most mobile devices. They inhibit navigability, search engine compatibility and printing functionality.',0,'trash','Mozilla/5.0 (Macintosh; Intel Mac OS X 10.6; rv:9.0.1) Gecko/20100101 Firefox/9.0.1','',0,1),(5,37,'Bill','bill.corrigan@acquitygroup.com','','127.0.0.1','2012-01-12 21:21:34','2012-01-12 21:21:34','Change this line:\n• Do not specify precise sizes for text fonts. Instead, use header tags (&lt;h1&gt;, &lt;h2&gt;, etc.) or use styles with font-size values in the em format.\n\nTo This\n• Where appropriate, use header tags (&lt;h1&gt;, &lt;h2&gt;, etc)\n\nChange this line:\n• Refrain from using frames. They are incompatible with certain browsers. They inhibit navigability, search engine compatibility and printing functionality.\n\nTo this:\n• Refrain from using frames. They are incompatible with certain browsers and most mobile devices. They inhibit navigability, search engine compatibility and printing functionality.',0,'1','Mozilla/5.0 (Macintosh; Intel Mac OS X 10.6; rv:9.0.1) Gecko/20100101 Firefox/9.0.1','',0,1),(6,39,'Bill','bill.corrigan@acquitygroup.com','','38.98.176.194','2012-01-17 15:25:26','2012-01-17 15:25:26','I would remove this section content from this document and just reference the separate browser support documents the team has. Or, if this document is often shown to clients as Eric Wood was just requesting it for, you could leave the section here but make it much more generic.\r\n \r\nWe were just going through this same discussion at my previous employer. The term we started using was “the most popular modern browsers”, then listed Internet Explorer, Mozilla/Firefox, and Safari (Chrome was just being added when I left).\r\n \r\nBy not listing a specific version, we won’t lock ourselves into updating this document every 6 weeks for Chrome and Firefox. We also won’t lock ourselves into supporting an unnecessary browser. By listing IE6 below we could potentially lock ourselves into supporting it when we don’t really need too. If the client’s site numbers show IE6 is less than 5% of their traffic, then we shouldn’t need to support it, and the client shouldn’t pay us for supporting it.\r\n\r\nAnother issue with listing all of the versions we support, how do we identify the versions of FireFox we support? Especially with their rapid  release schedule now (Chrome is much less of an issue because of their auto updates)? If we were to just go with the 5% number, we could run into an instance where 4, 6, 7, and 8 are above 5%, but version 5 is not. Do we say we support 4, but not 5?\r\n\r\nIn addition to saving us from supporting older browsers, it also leaves an opening for newer version of the browsers. In the current document, the list for IE was IE6, IE7, and IE8… but when did you start supporting IE9? In my previous positions, we supported a new version of a browser when it was officially released (with an exception). Even though they didn\'t have our official \"10% numbers\", we knew they were going to eventually.\r\n\r\nThe exception mentioned above was, we supported the newest version of the browser(s) if it was officially released before the project started. If IE9 was released 3 weeks into a 4 week project, we could/did not support it. If it was released 3 months into a 6 month project, then we\'d probably discuss it with the client and probably end up supporting it.\r\n\r\nSo maybe the term should be \"the most popular, modern, officially released browsers\". Someone else can probably come up with something better than that. My recommendation would be to identify the browser brands we support (Internet Explorer, FireFox, Safari, and Chrome), then identify versions of those browsers almost on a project by project basis, based on the analytics of their site. Some may require IE6 (and IE7, or others), some may not.\r\n\r\n===============\r\n\r\nBack up to the FireFox support and their rapid release schedule…\r\nI was trying to come up with a FF support standard for my previous employer, but hadn\'t quite made a decision when I left. I was leaning toward a \"newest version and back 2 or 3\" (i.e. version 8 is the most current, I think, so we would have supported 8, 7, 6, and maybe 5).',0,'1','Mozilla/5.0 (Macintosh; Intel Mac OS X 10.6; rv:9.0.1) Gecko/20100101 Firefox/9.0.1','',0,1);
